<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Poland-Thatcher 2ndLd-Writethru a0695 11-03 0859</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Poland-Thatcher, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0695,0882</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Thatcher: Western Aid Depends on Dialogue with Solidarity</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with Thatcher remarks at
banquet, embargo lifted. PICK up 12th pvs, St. Stanislaw. DELETES
final 3 grafs to TRIM.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto WAR50</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher
told Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski Thursday that the West would provide
financial aid to Poland when authorities begin ``real dialogue''
with Solidarity.
   Mrs. Thatcher made the comments to the Communist Party chief at a
banquet hours after she honored the memory of a slain pro-Solidarity
priest at a Warsaw church.
   Hundreds of supporters of the banned independent trade union
movement who had gathered at the church shouted to her that they
represent the real Poland.
   ``Here is Poland! Here is Poland!'' the crowd chanted as Mrs.
Thatcher walked into the yard of the St. Stanislaw Kostka Church to
lay a wreath on the grave of the Rev. Jerzy Popieluszko.
   At the banquet hosted by the Polish leader, Mrs. Thatcher said in
a toast that she was planning to go to Gdansk Friday to hear the
views of Solidarity leaders.
   She suggested that Jaruzelski too should listen to Solidarity,
which was outlawed after the imposition of martial law in 1981 but
is still the focal point of opposition to the communist government.
   ``Freedom and responsibility go hand in hand. Those who seek the
one must be prepared to offer the other,'' Mrs. Thatcher said.
``That is why it is so vital that there should be real dialogue with
representatives of all sections of society, including Solidarity.''
   For reforms to succeed, Mrs. Thatcher said, ``people have to be
involved in decisions about the way forward.''
   ``When that happens,'' she added, ``when that great day comes,
you will find your friends ready, not just to stand and cheer, but
to help in practical ways: by supporting a program with the IMF (the
International Monetary Fund), by offering credits, by rescheduling
debts, by encouraging investment and by establishing joint
ventures.''
   A British official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
prime minister's remarks could be seen as a reply to repeated
requests for aid from Britain in helping Poland cope with its
crushing $39 billion foreign debt.
   Jaruzelski responded that Poland had suffered greatly through its
history and Western countries which suffered less should not be too
quick to judge it.
   ``Our nation walked a thorny path. ... hence it knows well the
cost of security and stability of one's own state,'' he said in
remarks released in advance. ``No one today, looking from the
elevation of affluence .... should forget that.''
   Mrs. Thatcher and Jaruzelski conferred together for three hours
before the banquet, which culminated the second day of Mrs.
Thatcher's three-day state visit to Poland.
   The British official said Jaruzelski ``gave the impression that
he intended to embark on a radical set of reforms and acknowledged
these were essential.''
   Earlier Thursday, Mrs. Thatcher met with Prime Minister
Mieczyslaw F. Rakowski for a second time and visited a market.
   St. Stanislaw Kostka Church was the parish of Popieluszko, a
charismatic Roman Catholic priest who was abducted, beaten and
drowned in 1984 by four secret policemen who later were imprisoned.
   The crowd broke into a traditional hymn, ``God Watches Over
Poland,'' after Mrs. Thatcher placed the red, white and blue wreath
of roses, lilies and irises on the tombstone.
   The churchyard was lined with Solidarity banners, and an honor
guard of steelworkers stood by holding flags of the banned union.
   Shaking her head in apparent sadness, Mrs. Thatcher spoke with
Popieluszko's gaunt, elderly parents, Marianna and Wladyslaw.
   ``We are extremely grateful that she found the time to come
here,'' said Mrs. Popieluszko. ``We know that deep in her heart she
has been with our beloved son. We know she supports people suffering
in Poland.''
   Mrs. Thatcher, who is popular in Poland, has said she doesn't
want to interfere in Poland's internal affairs during her visit,
which began Wednesday. Both the opposition and the government have
been hoping to gain from her trip.
   The government would like Mrs. Thatcher's endorsement of tough
economic policies and her help with its debt crisis, while the
opposition hopes she will speak out for greater freedom.
   The government said Wednesday it was making a new approach to
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa about starting talks with the
opposition. Walesa said Thursday he would not reply to the approach
until after Mrs. Thatcher's departure Friday, but he said he would
continue to refuse to alter Solidarity's delegation to the talks,
which has been the stumbling block.
   ``She can give a push to the Polish government to come to terms
with reality, and reality is the existence of Solidarity,'' the
union's national spokesman Janusz Onyszkiewicz said in a British
television interview.
   In her talks with Rakowski, Mrs. Thatcher stonewalled an appeal
for Western aid, said a British official speaking on condition of
anonymity.
   Rakowski said the $39 billion foreign debt was ``like a noose
'round our necks,'' and appealed for Western help, the official
said. ``The prime minister did not respond,'' he said.
</TEXT>
