<HEAD>Grand Jury Indicts Former Firefighter on 16 Counts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LANCASTER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former firefighter accused of setting a
series of fires that terrorized a small town was indicted Thursday
on 14 counts of arson and two of attempted arson.
   Lance Lalumiere, 23, was arrested Oct. 12 on charges that he set
one of more than 20 fires that plagued Jefferson, a town of 850
people in northern New Hampshire, since May. Lalumiere had been
working as a dishwasher in the town.
   Authorities found a hand-drawn map of several arson sites in
Lalumiere's trailer and a propane torch in a car he owned, according
to court documents released earlier this week.
   A second Jefferson man was charged Oct. 13 with setting one fire
in Dalton, two towns from Jefferson. Though police initially said
firefighter Lawrence Coulter Jr., 19, was a suspect in other fires,
prosecutors said later they consider the Dalton fire an isolated
incident.
   The first fire Lalumiere was charged with setting was to his
brother Michael's cabin in Jefferson in late August.
   There have been no fires since the Oct. 3 fire in Dalton that
Coulter has been charged with setting.
   The attorney general's office said earlier that Lalumiere had
admitted to setting 16 fires.
   Since May 5, 26 fires have been set in the Jefferson area,
causing an estimated $1 million in property damage. The fires began
in brush and fields, but progressed to occupied homes and other
buildings. No one was killed, though there were close calls.
   Attorney General Stephen Merrill said prosecutors did not seek an
indictment Thursday against Coulter from the Coos County grand jury,
but would later.
   Asked if more arrests were expected, he said only, ``I can assure
you we are not going to conclude this matter until we are sure it's
finally resolved.''
</TEXT>
