<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AirSafety     11-03 0406</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Air Safety,390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Airline Safety Indicators Show Improvement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite steady traffic growth, airline safety
indicators showed a significant improvement during the first nine
months of the year compared with the same period last year, the
Transportation Department said Thursday.
   The department said the number of near-collision reports filed by
pilots as well as air traffic controller errors and airline fatal
accident rates all declined markedly during the period compared with
1987.
   Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said the improved safety
statistics came despite increased air traffic and coincide with
improved on-time performance by the major airlines.
   The department also made public Thursday its latest monthly
airline consumer scorecard which showed the 13 largest airlines have
had on-time records of 80 percent or better during each of the last
six months, including an 85.6 percent on-time arrival mark in
September.
   ``The statistics indicate that our efforts to improve airline
safety and service to consumers are reaping dividends,'' said
Burnley.
   The DOT said the number of near-collision reports from pilots
during the January-September period were 35 percent fewer _ 560
reports _ than filed during the same nine months in l987. The
announcement did not say and it could not be determined Thursday
night how many of the reports involved commercial airliners.
   During nine-month period, there also was a 15 percent decline
nationwide of air traffic controller errors in which aircraft were
allowed to come closer than legally allowed. While a near-collision
incident generally is reported only when planes come within 500
feet, a controller error can occur with aircraft as far as five
miles apart.
   The DOT said there were 808 reports of operational errors by
controllers during the January-September period, compared with 953
during the first nine months of l987.
   But officials acknowledged there were significant exceptions to
the national trend, particularly in the Chicago area, which has some
of the nation's busiest airspace.
   The Federal Aviation Administration recently reduced air traffic
in and out of the Chicago airports, including O'Hare International,
because of a sharp jump in controller errors. O`Hare controllers had
30 flight-handling errors between January and late October, compared
with 12 in all of 1987.
   Meanwhile, Burnley said there were 0.031 fatal accidents per
100,000 flying hours by regularly scheduled airlines during the
January-September period, compared with 0.041 per 100,000 hours in
the same nine months of l987, a decline of 24 percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
