<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 1920EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HospitalKidnapping     11-03 0506</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hospital Kidnapping,0521</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mother Says She Doesn't Hate Kidnapper But Wants Baby Back</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELISSA CONTI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A mother whose premature baby was stolen
from her hospital room pleaded publicly Thursday that the infant
needed immediate medical attention, and said she had no animosity
for the kidnapper.
   ``If the lady that took my child is listening, watching, I want
you to know that I love my child,'' Annette Jones-Thomas said in her
second public appeal to the woman who impersonated a nurse to take
the baby, Christopher Michael Jones.
   ``Well, let's say that Christopher is your child. What would you
do if your child was sick and needed immediate medical attention?
Would you leave your child at home to suffer, to die? Christopher
needs help now,'' she said.
   Mrs. Jones-Thomas read her statement slowly and deliberately,
appearing slightly nervous but speaking in a strong voice. Doctors
Hospital officials ended the news conference without allowing
reporters to question the mother.
   Rufus Thrower, Mrs. Jones-Thomas' doctor, said she was staying as
calm as possible.
   ``She is a very religious woman, deeply concerned in general
about people and I think it's her love for God and her family that's
kind of keeping her inner strength the way it is,'' Thrower said.
   Mrs. Jones-Thomas, who has two daughters, will be going home in
the next couple of days, Hall said.
   Police Lt. Bert Jenkins said detectives turned up nothing that
would lead them to the kidnapper and baby, who was born six weeks
premature on Saturday.
   The hospital offered a $10,000 reward and three other
organizations put up $1,000 each for the safe return of the child.
   Pediatricians said the boy, who weighed only 4 pounds, needed to
be fed every three hours and must be kept warm. ``If we were very,
very lucky, the baby could do well,'' Dr. Whit Hall said.
``Unfortunately, it could be dead now.''
   The kidnapper, wearing a white pleated skirt and a white sweater,
came into Mrs. Jones-Thomas' fourth-floor hospital room about 10
p.m. Tuesday as the mother was feeding the boy. The woman said she
had to weigh the baby and Mrs. Jones-Thomas gave her the child.
   When a nurse discovered the deception 30 minutes later, police
searched the area with dogs but found nothing.
   Hospital administrator Perry Kinder said he plans to re-evaluate
security, but feels it was adequate and that the kidnapping could
not have been anticipated.
   There was one security guard on duty Tuesday night, and four
hospital entrances were open, officials said.
   Police said they did not know why the Jones baby was taken from
among 28 babies on the same floor at the time of the kidnapping.
   Mrs. Jones-Thomas, 32, a secretary at the Arkansas Education
Association, described the kidnapper as black, about 20 years old,
5-foot-4, 135 pounds with shoulder length black hair.
   The baby was described as black, with long black hair, a large
growth on his right ear lobe and a small growth on his left lobe.
</TEXT>
