<1ST_LINE>r i AM-UN-ChemicalWeapons     11-03 0245</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Chemical Weapons,0251</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iraq Offers Help In Detecting Chemical Weapons Use</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iraq, which acknowledged using poison gas
in its war with Iran, is one of 17 nations willing to help
investigate allegations of chemical warfare in the world, according
to a U.N. document released Thursday.
   A report by Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar on chemical
and biological weapons summarizes U.N. efforts to develop ways of
detecting use of such weapons, mainly by coordinating the efforts of
experts in various nations.
   The report to the General Assembly includes the responses of 17
nations that have offered the use of laboratories or experts in
chemical warfare.
   Iraq offered the services of two doctors, two chemists and a
pharmacologist, but said ``it is not possible for Iraqi laboratories
to be used'' in chemical and biological warfare investigations.
   Last summer, Iraqi Foreign Minister Tariq Aziz answered a
question about alleged chemical warfare in the Persian Gulf war by
responding that Iraq used such weapons only after Iran used them
first.
   Iran says it has the ability to make chemical weapons, but has
never used them.
   Investigations by U.N. experts confirmed that Iraq used chemical
weapons against Iran throughout the war, which began in September
1980.
   Besides Iraq, other nations offering help were the United States,
the Soviet Union, Austria, Belgium, Brazil, Canada, Denmark,
Finland, France, West Germany, the Netherlands, New Zealand, Norway,
the Philippines, Spain, and Sweden.
</TEXT>
