<1ST_LINE>r p AM-TexasAds     11-03 0491</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texas Ads,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Justice Department To Examine Texas Ads Aimed At Hispanics</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh agreed
Thursday to investigate a Republican advertising campaign in South
Texas that Democrats claim is intimidating Spanish-speaking voters
with its ``Big Brother'' tone.
   ``We certainly will look into this complaint and to the extent
that there is any evidence that it might be valid, there will be a
harsh response from the federal government,'' said Justice
Department spokesman Loye Miller.
   Miller said the U.S. attorney in charge of the Lower Rio Grande
Valley would be contacted Friday and asked to ``take a look at the
whole situation.''
   Democratic Rep. Jack Brooks accused Texas Republicans Thursday of
using Spanish-language radio advertising to keep voters from going
to the polls next Tuesday in the heavily Hispanic border area by
``injecting an element of fear.''
   Brooks asked Thornburgh to determine if Republican Party
officials in Hidalgo County are violating federal voting rights laws
by running radio ads citing penalties for non-citizens who vote and
that twice remind listeners that election officials ``will be
watching.''
   Republican officials defend the ads as proper and say they are
not an attempt at intimidation.
   ``I would hope that any law enforcement agency spending time in
South Texas concentrates on trying to stamp out the voter fraud we
have seen in that region for the past 20 years _ voter fraud
perpetrated by the Democrats,'' said Mark Sanders, a spokesman for
the Texas campaign of Republican presidential nominee George Bush.
   Brooks, who is in line to become chairman of the House Judiciary
Committee, told Thornburgh in a letter: ``It should be clear that
this advertising campaign, accompanied by the repeated `Big Brother'
warning that `election officials are watching,' was not motivated by
the benign goal of discouraging illegal voting, but rather is an
obvious attempt to hold down overall voter turnout among
Spanish-speaking citizens by injecting an element of fear into the
voting process.''
   The Beaumont congressman said he believes the advertising could
be a violation of federal voting rights laws, which prohibit
intimidation or coercion in the exercise of the right to vote.
   Sanders said the ad is running in in Hidalgo County because ``we
don't want to see graveyard votes, Alice in Wonderland votes, and
votes from the precincts of outer Mongolia.''
   The Spanish language ad says: ``Voting officials will be watching
closely. It is illegal to vote in this election if you are not a
U.S. citizen. If you have a green card you cannot vote. If you do
you can be subject to up to 10 years in prison, fined up to $5,000
and lose your opportunity to become a U.S. citizen. If you accept
money to vote you can get up to five years in jail. Remember,
election officials are watching. Paid for by the Republican Party of
Hidalgo County, Don Winngate, director.''
</TEXT>
