<1ST_LINE>u i AM-PuertoRico-Quake 2ndLd-Writethru   11-03 0295</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Puerto Rico-Quake, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0735,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Earthquake Hits Puerto Rico</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with higher Richter scale
measurement, quake followed by aftershock, worst quake in 8 years.
PICK up 8th pvs, Last week.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake in northwest
Puerto Rico rippled across the Caribbean island, shaking buildings
and sending people running into the streets. No damage or injuries
were reported.
   An aftershock measuring 4 on the Richter scale followed the
quake, which measured 5.7, said William MacCann, director of the
University of Puerto Rico's Seismological Network.
   McCann said the 3:42 p.m. earthquake was the strongest in Puerto
Rico since 1979, when a temblor of magnitude 5.9 shook the island.
   He said the quake's epicenter was in the Atlantic Ocean off the
northwestern port city of Aguadilla, 80 miles west of San Juan. But
the tremor was felt throughout the island, which is 100 miles long
and 35 miles wide.
   In San Juan, where about one-third of the island's 3.2 million
people live, the tremor swayed some buildings and was felt for five
seconds. Puerto Rico is a U.S. commonwealth 1,100 miles southeast of
Florida.
   Anibal Roman, director for Civil Defense northwestern Puerto
Rico, said there were no reports of damage or injuries.
   A police official in Aguadilla said a housing project in the city
was evacuated and people ran yelling into the street.
   Last week, five earthquakes centered on an inactive volcano
struck the Caribbean island of St. Kitts, but caused no damage or
injuries.
   The Richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by an
earthquake, as measured by the ground motion released on a
seismograph.
   A quake of magnitude 4 can cause moderate damage. At magnitude 5,
it can cause considerable damage.
</TEXT>
