<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 2011EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 2ndLd-Writethru a0646 11-03 0689</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0646,690</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Sees `Awfully Short' Bush Honeymoon With Congress</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UDPATES with MacNeil-Lehrer appearance, INSERTING five grafs
after 15th pvs, The spot...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOUNT PLEASANT, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lloyd Bentsen said Thursday that if
Republican George Bush is elected president, his honeymoon with
Congress would be ``awfully short'' because of resentments stemming
from Bush's negative campaign tactics.
   ``I don't see how ... a president has any kind of a mandate if he
wins by the amount of negative advertising'' used by Bush, the
Democratic vice presidential candidate told reporters on a campaign
bus tour of East Texas.
   The Texas senator said he does not want a difficult relationship
with any new Republican administration, but that the ``concentration
on negative advertising, that doesn't become a mandate to the
American people.''
   ``That makes it more difficult,'' Bentsen said. ``You don't have
any so-called honeymoon. It would be an awfully short one, if you
had that.''
   Bentsen, who is chairman of the Senate Finance Committee, said
Bush as president might have particular trouble persuading Congress
to accept his campaign promise of a reduction in the top-bracket
capital gains tax rate from 33 percent to 15 percent.
   Bentsen said the proposal would benefit mostly the wealthy and
was regarded as a violation of the agreement behind the 1986 tax
overhaul law.
   Bentsen was interviewed in the lounge of a luxury bus he used
Thursday to stump for middle-class votes in the rural area of Texas
near the Louisiana and Arkansas borders.
   Two other buses and a few cars and pickup trucks chased the
candidate's vehicle through Longview, Daingerfield, Mount Pleasant,
Paris and Sulphur Springs. East Texas is rich in pro-Reagan
Democrats that party nominee Michael Dukakis must win in his bid for
the state's 29 electoral votes in Tuesday's balloting.
   ``I'm fighting for middle-income America and I'm standing up for
middle-income America,'' Bentsen told several hundred supporters in
Longview.
   ``When I'm vice president of the United States, and Michael
Dukakis is president of the United States, we'll meet with the press
on a regular basis,'' he said.
   ``And there's something else we'll do. We'll meet with the folks,
we'll meet with middle-income America,'' he said.
   ``That's the kind of accountability you want from your elected
representatives,'' he said, stressing the Democrats' accessibility
to voters and the media.
   By contrast, his GOP counterpart, Dan Quayle, is kept under
control ``like a parrot in a gilded cage,'' Bentsen said.
   Mike McCurry, Bentsen's press secretary, said the Democratic
campaign is releasing a new TV advertisement this weekend which
features Bentsen's widely publicized ``You're no Jack Kennedy'' barb
at Quayle during their mid-October debate.
   The spot ends with the words: ``President Quayle?'' he said.
   After his bus tour, Bentsen helicoptered into Dallas for a live
appearance on public television's MacNeil-Lehrer NewsHour, where he
said the main reason the Repulicans were leading in the polls was
their negative advertising.
   ``They've painted Michael Dukakis for something he isn't,''
Bentsen said, citing the criticism on gun control and the furlough
of Massachusetts prisoner Willie Horton, a convicted murderer who
brutalized a Maryland couple while on a weekend pass. Republican ads
has contended that Dukakis wanted to take away sportsmen's guns and
was soft on crime and that was not true, Bentsen said.
   He also reaffirmed his belief that there was a racist element in
the Republican use of the Horton case,
   But Bentsen said he felt the Democratic message was getting
through and there was still time to turn around the polls.
   ``I've been more encouraged in the last four days than I've been
in the last three months,'' he said.
   Among Bentsen's frequent stops Thursday was a visit to a
Daingerfield cafe for coffee and donuts.
   His bus had a special window installed so he could wave to
constituents. The vehicle, which belongs to a wealthy Texan who uses
it for family skiing trips, was not equipped with windows that open.
   Helping Bentsen draw crowds along the route were country music
singer Gary Morris and Hollywood actor Rob Lowe, who drew squeals
from young girls everywhere the caravan went.
</TEXT>
