<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Colombia-Army     11-03 0298</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Colombia-Army,0307</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>General Says Military Launching Total Offensive Against Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military is launching an offensive to
wipe out Colombia's leftist guerrillas, the country's top general
said Thursday.
   ``The subversives want a military response and we are going to
give it to them,'' Defense Minister Gen. Rafael Samudio Molina said
at a funeral for 11 soldiers killed in a guerrilla ambush Tuesday.
   ``As commander of the armed forces I exhort every single soldier
in a total offensive to destroy the enemy, eliminate him, wipe out
his will to fight,'' Samudio said.
   There are an estimated 10,000 leftist guerrillas in Colombia,
whose population of 30 million. More than 75,000 people have been
killed in 15 years of insurrection.
   Colombia's armed forces have held back from an all-out war
against the guerrillas during off-and-on peace talks between the
government and the rebels over the last six years.
   The army recently bought eight Blackhawk army helicopter gunships
from the United States for its anti-guerrilla forces.
   Samudio, apparently speaking with the support of President
Virgilio Barco, said there was no use trying to negotiate with the
guerrillas.
   The guerrillas rejected a peace plan proposed last month by
Barco, who offered pardons to all guerrillas who would surrender and
said he would let rebel leaders address Congress on changes that
should be made in Colombia.
   Barco's predecessor, President Belisario Betancur, launched peace
talks with the guerrillas in 1982. The talks collapsed amid mutual
accusations by the rebels and the military of cease-fire violations.
   In 50 separate actions last month, rebels raided towns and
military bases, ambushed army patrols and blew up bridges and high
tension electricity towers.
   By Defense Ministry count, 56 soldiers and policemen, 26
civilians and 123 rebels were killed.
</TEXT>
