<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle 2ndLd-Writethru a0777 11-03 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0777,720</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Quayle Says He Was Chosen Partly to ``Create Excitement''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 15th pvs, Quayle aides..., to give
Shannon statement.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Dan Quayle said Thursday that George
Bush picked him for the second spot on the Republican ticket at
least in part to ``create a little excitement'' at the GOP
convention.
   Grounded temporarily at the Owensboro airport while mechanics
replaced an auxiiary power unit on his campaign plane, Quayle,
standing in the lobby of the hangar, reflected on his campaign
experience.
   He said his reception by crowds at campaign rallies had given him
``a lot of exhilaration.'' On the other hand, he said, ``I guess my
biggest disappointment'' was what he called the ``totally unfair''
initial news media coverage of his candidacy.
   ``I'm willing to let bygones be bygones,'' he said. But Quayle
added that when the campaign is over, ``it's going to be a very
interesting discussion that you all are going to have about
yourselves.''
   If he could change anything about the campaign, Quayle said, he
would have skipped the post-New Orleans convention week in which he
was hit with ``harsh personal attacks ... about what I did 20 years
ago.''
   Quayle was faced with questions about the circumstances under
which he signed up for an Indiana National Guard unit in 1969,
during the Vietnam war, and about how he got admitted to the law
school with what basically was a ``C'' transcript from high school.
He has denied repeatedly that any improper influence was used in
either instance.
   On Thursday, Quayle acknowledged that he was mostly an unknown
commodity when Bush announced his selection on Aug. 16, the second
day of the GOP convention in New Orleans, and he said that the press
had a duty to scrutinize him.
   ``What he (Bush) wanted to do was create a little excitement at
the Republican convention,'' Quayle said.
   He grimaced when asked if that was the principal reason Bush
chose him, saying, ``no, also for my qualifications, experience and
so forth.''
   Quayle also referred to the close supervision and handling he got
from representatives of the Bush campaign in the weeks immediately
following the New Orleans convention.
   ``I never like to Monday morning quarterback,'' he said, ``I
would have made the change of not having a a controlled environment
earlier. But that was a decision I had to make myself.''
   Quayle, who told reporters several weeks ago that he was
declaring his independence from such tight control, also said
Thursday, however, he recognized a need for special handling
initially ``because I didn't know the ground rules'' of running a
national campaign.
   In a speech prepared later at a rally attended by more than 4,000
people on the campus of Oklahoma State University, Quayle said that
Michael Dukakis' tough position on drugs ``rings hollow.''
   He said that ``Mr. Dukakis is coming out with a lot of tough talk
about a war on drugs.'' Then, Quayle quoted Massachusetts Attorney
General James Shannon, a Democrat, as saying five months ago:
``We're losing the war on drugs in the Commonwealth of
Massachusetts.''
   Quayle aides said that Mitchell had made the statement in a June
10 article in The New York Times.
   ``If Mr. Dukakis can't fight drugs effectively in his own
backyard, how can he make claims to do so for America,'' the senator
asked.
   Shannon issued a statement through the Dukakis campaign, saying:
``The reason we have a drug problem in Massachusetts and 49 other
states is because George Bush blew the one job Ronald Reagan gave
him, and that was to spearhead the administration's war on drugs.
   ``While Gov. Dukakis led the nation in bringing early drug
education into the schools and spending more money on drug
enforcement, George Bush was asleep at the wheel.''
   In Kentucky, Quayle, his aides, Secret Service agents and the
traveling press corps spent more than three hours at the terminal
before boarding the Boeing 727 for the flight to South Carolina.
   At one point, the senator, accompanied by a small group of
reporters, was driven to the Town Square Mall in Owensboro and to
Thornbury's toy store to shop for his son Benjamin, who turns 12
Saturday.
   Quayle visited with employees while he shopped, exclaimed ``this
is Reaganomics at work'' when he spotted a toy on sale and paid his
$51.42 bill with a credit card.
</TEXT>
