<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-03 0457</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0467</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Blankets Yellowstone, Washington Cascades, But Southern Plains
Warm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press_</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Up to a foot of snow fell Thursday at the south entrance of
Yellowstone National Park and strong winds hit Colorado, Wyoming and
the northern coast of New England, but the southern Plains and Texas
were warm.
   Snow advisories were in place Thursday over the higher elevations
of the Washington Cascades, with a snowfall of 6 inches at Chinook
Pass and 7 inches at Washington Pass.
   In Yellowstone, 2 inches of snow covered southern portions and
the Snowy Range Ski Area, and 8 to 12 inches fell near the south
entrance. In New Hampshire, 4 inches fell at Mount Washington.
   High wind warnings were posted over southeast Wyoming and parts
of Colorado, where gusts were expected to reach 70 or 80 mph, the
National Weather Service said. Morning winds were recorded at 57 mph
at Boulder and 54 mph at the Air Force Academy. In Wyoming, winds
gusted to 62 mph at Washoe Valley and to 78 mph in the nearby
mountains.
   A wind advisory was posted over the mountains of northern
California Thursday afternoon and night. Warnings of gale force
winds remained Thursday night along the northern coast of New
England.
   Temperatures through the southern Plains remained warm, and
Abilene, Texas, tied a high temperature record for the date set in
1897 with an 84 degree reading. San Angelo, Texas, set a new record
with 86 degrees, breaking the former record of 85 degrees in 1915.
   The low in the nation early Thursday was 16 degrees at Alamosa,
Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 2 p.m. EST ranged from 32
degrees at Saranac Lake, N.Y., to 86 degrees at Fort Meyers, Fla.
   For Friday, the forecast called for widespread showers and
occasional thunderstorms extending from Louisiana to the Florida
Panhandle and over most of the Appalachians, the Tennessee and Ohio
valleys, Illinois and eastern Missouri.
   Showers are expected to reach from eastern North Dakota across
the Great Lakes to New Jersey, New York and southern New England.
Rain showers also are forecast from western Montana across Idaho and
Washington, changing to snow in the higher elevations.
   Winds will be strong and gusty over the Rockies and the Texas
panhandle. Temperatures will reach the 40s and 50s over northern and
central New England, the upper Great Lakes and from the upper
Mississippi Valley across the northern Rockies and Washington.
   Highs will be in the 80s over much of the Florida peninsula, much
of Louisiana and from much of Texas across southeast Arizona. Highs
will be in the 80s and low 90s over the desert Southwest. High
temperatures over the remainder of the nation will generally reach
the 60s and 70s.
</TEXT>
