<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Chile-Generals     11-03 0289</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile-Generals,0301</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Reshuffles Army, Retires 12 Generals</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Chile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet reshuffled the
highest ranks of his army on Thursday, sending a dozen generals into
retirement.
   An army communique listed among the 12 Lt. Gen. Santiago
Sinclair, deputy commander-in-chief and considered a staunch
supporter of Pinochet.
   Pinochet, the army commander-in-chief, named Maj. Gen. Jorge
Zincke as deputy, the man who handles the day-to-day business in the
service while Pinochet devotes most of his time to the presidency.
   As commander of Santiago garrison, Zincke was widely credited
with mantaining order during the Oct. 5 referendum, when voters
rejected a proposal by the military that Pinochet extend his 15
years in power until 1997. Zincke's performance that day drew praise
even from some opposition leaders.
   Zincke is considered less a hardliner than his predecessor,
Sinclair, who was noted by his fervent personal loyalty to Pinochet.
   The highly disciplined army has been considered the backbone of
Pinochet's power since he led the military in a 1973 coup.
   The communique said four of the generals had reached mandatory
retirement with 40 years in service. Pinochet retired the other
eight because of undisclosed ``institutional reasons'' as part of an
annual process, it said.
   Pinochet used special legislation to let Gen. Sergio Badiola, a
close friend and Santiago governor, stay in the army despite
reaching retirement age. Among those retired for ``institutional
reasons'' was Gen. Ernesto Videla, who has been a deputy foreign
minister for years and is considered a highly popular officer among
his peers and among many civilian politicians.
   Pinochet also promoted 10 brigadiers to the rank of general.
   Pinochet personally announced the changes to the entire generals
corps during a luncheon at the Presidential Palace.
</TEXT>
