<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GunBan-Blacks     11-03 0525</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gun Ban-Blacks,0538</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>NRA, Black Establishment Clash Over Gun Referendum</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ROLL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maryland's urban black precincts are shaping up
as the crucial battleground in the final days of a bitter referendum
fight over the state's pioneering handgun law.
   The importance of the black areas was underscored Thursday when
Jesse Jackson gave a passionate endorsement of the law in a rally at
predominately black Morgan State University.
   Before the rally, Jackson told WBAL Radio, ``I support people
having guns on reservations to hunt game. I support people having
the right to guns in their houses, but not to have guns to hunt
other people. ... I say let's stop the guns and stop the drugs and
let's go another way.''
   The 6-month-old law, designed to outlaw cheap pistols known as
Saturday Night Specials, creates a nine-member board with authority
to outlaw the sale and manufacture of handguns it deems don't have
legitimate uses for recreation or personal security.
   The Jackson appearance was an attempt to undercut the strategy
pro-gun forces hope will result in the law's repeal next Tuesday:
win big in the state's rural areas, break even in the white suburbs
and keep the margin down in black precincts.
   According to a Mason-Dixon poll conducted Oct. 29-30, blacks, who
are 22 percent of the Maryland electorate, support the law 55
percent to 29 percent with 16 percent still undecided. No margin of
error was given for that part of the poll because the sampling was
small.
   Overall, Marylanders favor the law approximately 48 percent to 44
percent with 9 percent undecided, according to the poll. The poll's
overall margin of error was 3.5 percentage points.
   Advocates of repeal argue the law would open the door to
banishment of all handguns. That message is being given to black
voters, along with the argument the law discriminates against the
poor because it would make inexpensive weapons unavailable.
   The law's suporters counter by noting that guns are the leading
cause of death among young black men in Maryland and insisting it
will make the streets of their communities safer.
   The law's opponents acknowledge that their cause has been damaged
by an inability to garner the support of high-profile black leaders,
a fact they blame on pressure from the white political establishment.
   ``If we had had an even break in terms of power structure
endorsements, we would have been over the top already,'' said George
Young, a California political consultant who is directing the repeal
effort.
   ``There is a linkage between black politicians and white liberals
having to do with political fund raising ... and to the extent
(black) people are philosophically or economically committed to
being friends with the liberal structure, they just can't afford to
take a stand against this structure,'' Young said.
   That analysis infuriated James Abraham, who is leading the
pro-law campaign in black areas.
   ``That's racist, really. It infers we don't have any political
integrity. It's nasty and I don't like it,'' Abraham said.
   Abraham, in turn, charged the pro-gun forces with trying to buy
the votes of blacks by hiring blacks to do door-to-door canvassing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
