<HEAD>Judge To Hear Evidence in Adams Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man whose murder conviction in the slaying of a
Dallas police officer drew national attention because of questions
raised in the documentary movie ``The Thin Blue Line'' has a chance
at a new trial.
   State District Judge Larry Baraka on Wednesday agreed to hear
arguments from attorneys that new evidence, some of which was
allegedly suppressed during his original trial, proves Randall Dale
Adams did not kill the Dallas officer.
   ``I felt there was a sufficient amount of issues raised to cause
the court concern enough to look into it,'' Baraka said.
   After hearing evidence Nov. 30, Baraka will tell the Texas Court
of Criminal Appeals whether he believes Adams deserves a new trial.
The appeals court is the only Texas court that has the power to
grant such a trial.
   In 1977, Adams was convicted of killing officer Robert Wood, who
was shot to death on a nearly deserted street Nov. 28, 1976.
   Adams' attorney, Randy Schaffer, contends that Adams is innocent
and that the real killer was David Ray Harris, the state's key
witness against him. In statements to newspapers and in the movie
``The Thin Blue Line,'' Harris has said Adams is innocent.
   Harris is on Death Row for a different killing.
   Dallas County District Attorney John Vance said his office would
contest the motion and dismissed Harris' statements, saying he is
simply seeking publicity.
   Adams originally was sentenced to death, but Gov. Bill Clements
in 1979 commuted his term to life.
</TEXT>
