<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Obit-Folsey     11-03 0218</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Obit-Folsey,0226</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>George Folsey, Noted Cinematographer, Dead at 90</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cinematographer George Folsey, who
was nominated for 13 Academy Awards during a career that spanned 50
years, has died after a stroke and long illness. He was 90.
   Folsey died Tuesday at St. John's Hospital.
   He was best known for his collaborations with directors Vincente
Minelli, George Cukor, Frank Capra, Ernst Lubitsch, Rouben Mamoulian
and Busby Berkeley.
   Among the films Folsey shot were the Marx Brothers' ``Animal
Crackers,'' Capra's ``State of the Union,'' Minelli's ``Meet Me in
St. Louis'' and the television series ``The Fugitive.''
   In 1976, he returned to motion pictures to film special footage
of Fred Astaire and Gene Kelly for ``That's Entertainment, Part 2.''
   His Oscar nominations included ``Executive Suite,'' ``Seven
Brides for Seven Brothers'' and ``The Balcony.'' He also served as
president of the American Society of Cinematographers in the late
1950s.
   He is survived by his wife of 61 years, Angele; a son George Jr.,
a producer-editor who was acquitted in last year's ``Twilight Zone''
involuntary manslaughter trial; and two grandchildren.
   A mass and burial is set for 10:30 a.m. Saturday at St. Paul the
Apostle Church in Westwood. A wake is scheduled Friday at 7:30 p.m.
at the Santa Monica funeral home of Gates Kingsley & Gates.
</TEXT>
