<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Algeria 4thLd-Writethru a0805 11-03 0582</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Algeria, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0805,0595</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Algerians Approve Political Reforms Inspired by Riots</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 5th graf, A month, with 1 graf to CORRECT turnout figure,
83.08 sted 82.82. Picks up 6th graf pvs, Bendjedid voted.</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Algerians on Thursday massively approved
a series of constitutional changes, inspired by bloody riots a month
ago, to loosen the grip of the sole political party on national life
and separate it from the government.
   The Interior Ministry announced early Friday that 92.72 percent
of those who voted said yes to the changes proposed by President
Chadli Bendjedid.
   The referendum is the first step in reforms that eventually may
permit independent candidates to run for office and remove the
state-run economy from central control.
   The ruling National Liberation Front led the fight that won
independence from France in 1962 and has controlled the North
African country's political, economic, social, cultural and judicial
affairs ever since.
   A month after riots rocked Algeria, voters peacefully cast
ballots at 36,775 polling stations throughout the country. Turnout
was put at 83.08 percent of Algeria's 12 million voters.
   Bendjedid voted soon after polls opened at the Ghazali school in
the El Mouradia section of Algiers.
   At the Concorde School for Boys in the Bir Mouradais
neighborhood, businessman Joubi Wacer placed his ballot in a brown
voting box and said: ``It's the beginning of change. After this,
things will be different. At least I hope so.''
   Crowds of young men and a few veiled, elderly women walked to and
from the school, where a single blue-uniformed guard stood by the
gate. There was no indication of special security in the capital and
shoppers filled downtown streets in the late afternoon.
   Last month, soldiers and police fired on mobs of young men,
killing 176 people by official count during the week of riots.
Unofficial reports put the number of dead at 400 or more.
   Demonstrators in Algiers and provincial cities were protesting
food shortages, unemployment and a decline in the standard of living
blamed on the plummeting price of oil, Algeria's chief export.
   In a televised speech at the time, Bendjedid tried to ease the
unrest by promising a greater voice to people outside the National
Liberation Front.
   Kamel Belkacem, publisher of the pro-reform weekly newspaper
Algerie Actualite, said the proosals on Thursday's ballot were
designed to ``put an end to the party's power monopoly, and they
offer the challenge of democracy to the country. It's extraordinary,
a veritable revolution for Algeria.''
   Belkacem said in an interview that he expected the country to
enter a period of ``democratic apprenticeship'' after the vote.
   In presenting the referendum as a first step, Bendjedid said
further changes would be considered by a party congress later this
month and submitted to voters in another referendum next year.
   The National Liberation Front will remain the sole legal party,
but Belkacem said he believes the president's ultimate goal is free
and open elections.
   Several provisions in Thursday's referendum make subtle but
important changes that separate the government from the party. For
instance, new wording in the constitution would say the president
``incarnates the unity of the nation'' rather than ``incarnates the
unity of the ... party and the state.''
   Some powers, not specified, would be shifted from the president
to the premier, who would answer to the parliament for his
government's policies. The premier now answers only to the
president, and in practice has only limited authority.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
