<1ST_LINE>u a AM-MarcosBail 1stLd-Writethru a0750 11-03 0902</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Marcos Bail, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0750,0925</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Precede HONOLULU</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Marcos: I Will Comply With Fingerprints Order</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Leads with 15 grafs to UPDATE with exclusive Marcos interview,
his saying he will obey order; other quotes, comment; picks up 5th
graf: ``Assistant U.S. ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Philippine President Ferdinand Marcos said
Thursday he will comply with a federal judge's order that he and his
wife Imelda submit their fingerprints, voice prints and handwriting
samples to a grand jury.
   ``I'll take my destiny, whatever that may be, but I'm going to
fight for my dignity and honor,'' Marcos told The Associated Press
in an exclusive interview, his first meeting with the press since
being indicted two weeks ago on racketeering charges.
   U.S. District Judge John Walker ordered the former president and
first lady of the Philippines to appear Wednesday at the FBI's
offices in Honolulu to comply with the subpoenas.
   If they don't, said Walker, ``the Marcoses, both Ferdinand and
Imelda, must appear before me on Nov. 10 for imposition of
sanctions.''
   Marcos, accused with his wife of plundering more than $100
million from their homeland and spending it in the United States,
said he would meet his legal obligations and had been offered no
promises by the federal government.
   ``No, I am not afraid of going to jail,'' said Marcos, who sat in
a wheelchair during the interview. ``I would probably be dead by the
time the trial is over. I'm feeling in pain every day.''
   The Marcoses and eight others were indicted after more than two
years' investigation. Other grand juries here and in West Virginia
are still investigating Marcos, but he said he was sure he would be
vindicated.
   ``I don't think they have any evidence,'' said Marcos, citing
past investigations in the United States, the Philippines and Japan
which he said cleared him of similar charges.
   Marcos did not say whether he would testify before a
congressional subcommittee investigating allegations that he
illegally funneled millions of dollars into President Reagan's 1980
and 1984 campaign funds, but denied the accusations.
   ``We never contributed to any political activities in the United
States and the Federal Elections Commission reached that same
conclusion,'' he said.
   Marcos, 71, said he held no hard feelings for President Reagan,
who had hailed Marcos as a staunch U.S. ally and allowed the
Marcoses to settle here after their fall from power in February 1986.
   ``It's nothing personal ... we just feel that the worship of the
Statue of Liberty may have been displaced,'' Marcos said. ``We feel
betrayed by an American system that we believed to be fair and just
... now it seems that is not true.''
   Mrs. Marcos pleaded innocent in New York on Monday, but her
husband's arraignment was postponed pending a report by a government
physician who examined him the same day.
   Defense lawyers contend Marcos is too frail for the 10-hour
flight to New York and the interview with the AP was cut short by
aides who said Marcos was late for a medical appointment.
   During Thursday's hearing at federal court in New York City,
which Mrs. Marcos did not attend, Walker did not specify what
sanctions he would impose but said he would ``hold in abeyance the
issuance of a bench warrant'' for their arrests.
   Assistant U.S. Attorney Linda Imes, in arguing that the material
was still needed despite the couple's indictment last month and Mrs.
Marcos' fingerprinting this week, revealed ``there is an ongoing
investigation'' by the grand jury.
   She would reveal no more in open court, citing grand jury secrecy
laws.
   Marcos lawyer Sandor Frankel said the couple sought a stay
earlier in the day from U.S. Supreme Court Justice Thurgood Marshall.
   After earlier losses in the legal wrangle before Walker and the
2nd U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in New York, the Marcoses are
seeking a hearing before the Supreme Court and asked Marshall to
stay any action against them until the high court decides on whether
to hear their case, said Frankel.
   ``Barring a stay, they will comply with (Walker's) order,''
Frankel told reporters after the hearing.
   The Marcoses were indicted on racketeering charges by a federal
grand jury in Manhattan Oct. 21 for allegedlly diverting more than
$100 million from their nation's treasury into Swiss bank accounts,
Manhattan real estate and fine art.
   The same grand jury subpoenaed the couple earlier this year for
fingerprints, palm prints, voice and handwriting samples and also
for their authorization for foreign banks to turn over their
financial records.
   The Marcoses balked, claiming they still maintained
``head-of-state immunity,'' but Walker dismissed that claim and
found them in contempt of court in August.
   A federal appeals court upheld Walker's finding and reinstated
the contempt finding as well as an arrest warrant for the Marcoses.
   ``It's the government's position that it's now time for
compliance with these subpoenas,'' Ms. Imes told Walker.
   She requested that if the couple did not comply by Monday, they
be arrested and jailed.
   But Frankel said: ``President and Mrs. Marcos will comply with
their legal obligations,'' adding, ``There's no need for any warrant
to compel their compliance.''
   Mrs. Marcos was arraigned and pleaded innocent to the
racketeering charges Monday. Her exact whereabouts were unknown
although she was believed to be visiting with tobacco heiress Doris
Duke, who posted more than $5 million in bonds as bail for her
friend.
</TEXT>
