<DOCNO> AP881103-0219 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 2357EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FernaldPollution     11-03 0517</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Fernald Pollution,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>State Cites New Health Threat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Department of Energy documents filed in
court show evidence of previously undisclosed releases of
radioactive materials into groundwater from the Fernald uranium
processing plant, state officials say.
   More radioactive radium was released into an aquifer under the
plant than had been realized, increasing the potential health threat
to nearby residents, state officials said. The Great Miami aquifer
provides water to some southwestern Ohio communities and businesses
near Fernald, 18 miles northwest of Cincinnati.
   Ohio Environmental Protection Agency officials said they learned
of increased radium releases into the Great Miami River system and
into waste pits at the plant from documents in a $300 million,
class-action lawsuit that neighbors of the plant filed against its
former operator, National Lead of Ohio Inc.
   ``It's definitely new stuff. We're not aware of it,'' Ohio EPA
spokesman Graham Mitchell said Wednesday. He said the state EPA did
not know radium had ever been dumped into the waste pits at the Feed
Materials Production Center plant's 1,050-acre site.
   The documents, filed by the U.S. Department of Energy, are part
of the defense the department has prepared for National Lead of Ohio
Inc., the 37-year-old plant's operator prior to 1985, when
Westinghouse Materials Co. took over.
   The residents sued in U.S. District Court three years ago,
contending NLO allowed radioactive uranium dust to escape from the
plant, damaging their health and property. The Energy Department
says NLO was innocent because the company was ordered by Energy
Department officials to violate environmental regulations in favor
of increasing production.
   Energy Department officials have refused to close the Fernald
plant, saying its operations do not pose environmental dangers or
put nearby residents at risk. But the department has begun a
10-year, $500 million clean-up and modernization effort.
   News of the radium releases, which the documents say occurred
between 1966 and 1974, comes after politicians and environmentalists
responded angrily to recent reports of greatly increased estimates
of the amounts of uranium dust released by the plant into the
atmosphere. Radium is a byproduct of decaying uranium.
   ``Day after day it's another revelation, one worse than the
other,'' U.S. Rep. Thomas Luken, D-Ohio, said. ``It's like the
Chinese water torture.''
   Luken said he would ask the U.S. EPA to inspect the plant
immediately.
   The documents reviewed by Ohio EPA were reports and letters
written by officials from the Energy Department and NLO Inc. They
indicated that releases of radium into the Great Miami River had
exceeded water-pollution standards in effect at the time, Ohio EPA
officials say.
   Plant managers also worried about the amount of radium they were
dumping into a waste pit at the site, the documents said.
   Steve Wyatt, a spokesman for the Energy Department, said the
amount of radium put into the pit was minuscule.
   The plant is one of 16 nationally that produce nuclear weapons
materials for the Department of Energy.
   Several other plants, including Savannah River in Georgia and the
Rocky Falts plant near Denver, are in various stages of shutdown
while investigations are conducted into health and safety problems.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
