<1ST_LINE>a i PM-GandhiCampaign Adv08   11-03 0601</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gandhi Campaign, Adv 08,0615</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv08</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Tues PMs Nov. 8 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>With Eye Toward Elections, Rajiv Gandhi Becomes TV Figure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With his political opposition in
disarray, Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi has been traveling about the
country meeting the people and cameras of the government-run
television network have been close behind.
   Gandhi is not required to call an election until the end of 1989,
but speculation is mounting in the press that he will call what is
known as a ``snap'' election as early as March to take advantage of
the disorder in opposition ranks.
   Some Indians see television as a factor that could help Gandhi
counter his fall in popularity in recent years. An opinion poll in
August indicated a united opposition could easily defeat Gandhi's
long-entrenched Congress Party and deny him another five-year term.
   In recent days millions of people in cities and villages have
watched on television sets as Gandhi toured violence-torn Punjab or
trekked through mud and water to villages inundated by flash floods,
his Italian-born wife Sonia a step behind.
   The scenes have become a regular part of the 20-minute Hindi-and
English-language newscasts on the government-run television network
Doordarshan.
   When Gandhi came to power following the assassination of his
mother, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi, four years ago, television's
influence spanned less than 20 percent of the country. But his
closest aides immediately recognized its importance.
   ``His mother used television mainly for political purposes _
important rallies and speeches and her trips aboard,'' said Ashis
Nanday, a political analyst with the Center for the Study of
Developing Societies.
   ``Her son has taken it one step farther, using it to project
himself not only as a leader but as a person. To a large number of
Indians, he is the first Indian prime minister who is also a
television personality.''
   Today, television is available in almost 75 percent of the
country. The entire country will be within reach of Doordarshan's
transmitters by the end of next year, when an election must be
called.
   Gandhi's travels before the camera come as a fractious and
pugnacious opposition is trying to rally under the green flag of the
Janata Dal (People's Party).
   Janata Dal, a patchwork of three regional parties, is pinning its
hopes on Viswanath Pratap Singh, a former Gandhi ally and now one of
the prime minister's most vocal critics. But the new coalition party
has been beset by bickering, internal power struggles and
accusations of corruption and nepotism.
   After the opinion poll suggested a united opposition could unseat
Gandhi in the upcoming elections, the biweekly magazine India Today
wrote of Janata Dal: ``While its leaders pontificate piously about
the evils of the Rajiv Gandhi government, they themselves are no
angels. And as they spit and bark and growl at each other in a
public display of pettiness that passes off for `unity talks' they
do themselves, the voters and the nation a grave disservice.''
   The poll, conducted for India Today, indicated Gandhi's
popularity had plunged to an all-time low and that if the opposition
could come together and remain united, it would be within striking
distance of ousting the Congress Party, which has governed for all
but 29 months of India's 42 years as an independent nation.
   But the poll also indicated that nearly two-thirds of the 13,000
voters questioned didn't know the 54-year-old Singh, the
opposition's leading candidate.
   Singh seemed unconcerned, however.
   ``I have patience,'' he said. ``Let me exhaust my weapons before
I show my trump card.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Tues PMs Nov. 8</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881103-0224 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 1139EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a i PM-Italy-SavingtheSea Adv09   11-03 0809</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Italy-Saving the Sea, Adv 09,0827</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wed PMs Nov. 9 or Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Italy Making a Start on Saving Seas Around It</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>USTICA, Sicily (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two bright yellow buoys in the cobalt blue
sea around this volcanic island protect an increasingly endangered
Italian treasure _ clear, clean water and the rich marine life in it.
   The buoys also mark one of the government's first efforts to save
the seas that surround Italy _ the Ligurian, Tyrrhenian, Adriatic,
Ionian and Mediterranean.
   From sea floor to surface, from shore to three miles out, the
crystalline waters surrounding Ustica, an island about 35 miles
north of Sicily, have been decreed a natural marine reserve.
   Along with a small corner of the Adriatic near Trieste to the
north, Ustica was the first to enjoy special protection under a
decree by the environmental and merchant marine ministries in
November 1986.
   The decree called for 18 more reserves _ among them Sardinia's
sapphire seas and the thermal waters of the Aeolian Islands off
Sicily's northeast coast. But so far Ustica and Trieste are the only
ones to be created.
   In Ustica's case, the buoys mark a slice of the reserve in which
just about every activity is forbidden: fishing from boats or
underwater, boating and even swimming, except for two small inlets
where bathing is permitted. Local authorities can restrict fishing
permits for the rest of the island's waters, and undersea fishing is
forbidden around half of the island.
   Ustica's volcanic rocks and caves snare plankton carried by
strong, cold Atlantic currents entering the Mediterranean through
Gibraltar to the southeast and flow by the island. Plankton, tiny
forms of sea life, are key links in the food chain for the island's
exotic undersea greenhouse-menagerie. The results are 24-hour
undersea dining rooms as colorful as found in the tropics.
   Some samples from the sea swim in three fish tanks set up in an
18th-century stone guard tower on a bluff overlooking the reserve.
   Each tank represents a different depth of the sea. There are
crimson ``sea tomatoes,'' which look like jelly apples, spindly
orange coral and ``sea roses'' _ creatures that seem like flowers
spun out of delicate pink lace. There are urchins, too, although
fishing and disease have whittled down their numbers.
   Visitors can also see a slide show about fish too large for the
tanks as well as strange denizens of the deep such as a sex-changing
fish and ``sea spaghetti,'' a plant that winds up in local salads.
   For 30 years, the island, with its spectacularly clear waters,
has hosted gatherings of the world's top divers and undersea
specialists, including the legendary Jacques Costeau.
   Ustica's waters once abounded in large stone bass, but no longer.
Fishing with drag nets and indiscriminate catches by underwater
fishermen have cut down the population of the species.
   The World Wildlife Fund in Italy, which manages the Trieste
reserve, estimates that the planned total of 20 reserves would
protect barely 2 percent of Italy's coastal waters. Counting the two
reserves and other small stretches of seashore watched over by
environmental groups, the WWF says only 40 miles of Italy's 5,000
miles of coastline now have some kind of protection.
   ``We can't wait 10 years'' for the other 18 reserves, says
Antonio Canu, of the WWF's Rome office. ``The sea will be ruined.''
   This summer was especially harsh for Italian waters. In July,
bathers had to abandon a fashionable Tuscan beach for a week after
an explosion at a pesticide plant spilled toxic chemicals over a
stretch of Italy's northwest coast.
   On the east coast, gondoliers and their tourist clients in Venice
endured the stench of decaying algae, which flourished on tons of
untreated industrial and human garbage pouring into the lagoon.
   For environmentalists, Ustica is an intelligent marriage of
nature and tourism.
   Mayor Nicola Longo sees the reserve as a chance to control
possible damage from tourism, which is relatively new to Ustica.
   Until the 1950s, Ustica's guests were few and included suspected
Mafiosi sent into exile; before that, opponents of the Mussolini's
Fascist regime were confined on the island. They included Antonio
Gramsci, a founder of the Italian Communist Party, who recalled in
letters from Ustica that the islanders hadn't heard of radio when he
arrived in 1926.
   Like the mayor, who also makes the island's only wine for sale,
many of the 1,200 islanders have two or more jobs or enterprises _
restaurant owners catch their customers' fish, part-time fishermen
tend hillsides terraced with grapes or capers and fenced off by rows
of prickly pear trees.
   Usticesi, as the islanders are known, leave the island to go to
high school in Palermo on Sicily. Many of them never come back,
except for summers, since work is scarce on the island.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Wed PMs Nov. 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881103-0225 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 1010EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a PM-AnotherLook:DartmouthPresident ADV07   11-03 1051</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Another Look: Dartmouth President, ADV 07,1082</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv07</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Monday PMs, Nov. 7, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Freedman's First Year: Change And A New Focus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WENDY MITMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HANOVER, N.H. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When James Freedman took over as president
of Dartmouth College last year, many on campus and among the alumni
anticipated another in a line of reserved, don't-make-waves leaders.
   Surprise.
   Unafraid to stir hornets' nests, Freedman has made his mission
clear: ridding Dartmouth of what some call its ``smart jock'' image
and revealing the school as a haven for gifted students, top-notch
faculty and ``creative loners.''
   He's also taken on an off-campus student newspaper whose hardline
conservative stands and activism have brought Dartmouth publicity it
doesn't want.
   Though most faculty members, trustees and alumni seem pleased
with Freedman, critics warn that the first president snce 1822 with
no prior connection to this Ivy League school is trying to create a
``North Harvard,'' a Dartmouth alien to its own traditions and
history.
   Freedman, 52, a Harvard graduate with a law degree from Yale,
came to the college about 130 miles northwest of Boston in July
1987. A former president of the University of Iowa and dean of the
University of Pennsylvania's law school, he now presides over about
4,800 students who pay $13,300 a year.
   Shortly after arriving, he made clear his aggravation with the
image of Dartmouth students as ``extroverted, gregarious,
party-going, athletically oriented, overly prone to conformity,
well-rounded and intelligent _ but not intellectual.''
   ``That stereotype doesn't describe the Dartmouth student body as
a whole,'' he said in an interview. ``I see people who are writing
novels, I see people who are acting in plays, I see people who are
making films ...''
   Freedman wants to attract more top scholars, women and
minorities; broaden exchange programs with foreign universities; and
enhance the life of the faculty by letting members expand their
study and research.
   He began the ``Presidential Scholars'' program, flying in top
high school scholars who were considering Dartmouth and offering
them VIP treatment. Of 201 students targeted, 63 chose Dartmouth
this year _ double the enrollment of top scholars last year.
   The program also increased the number of women and minorities _
the current freshmen class is 45 percent women, up from 38 percent.
About 25 percent of the freshmen are minority students, up about 2
percent.
   But critics question Freedman's programs.
   ``Why do you persist in turning Dartmouth College into an
elitist, intellectual, international university?'' Hobart Van
Deusen, a 1958 alumnus, asked in a letter in the Alumni Magazine.
``Why do you not preserve Dartmouth traditions?''
   Jeffrey Hart, an English professor and faculty member since 1963,
said Frn't know that Dartmouth needs that.''
   A diverse, 18-member search committee unanimously chose Freedman
from 619 applicants, and explained search chairman Norman
McCullough, ``In James Freedman, the clear indication was that we
were looking for an academician, one who would lead the faculty in a
collegial style, and really one who could capitalize on an
institution that was ripe for the next phase of growth.''
   ``I don't think there's any intention to change the basic
character of Dartmouth,'' said George Munroe, who succeeded
McCullough as chairman of the college trustees.
   ``If we can upgrade its intellectual distinction _ which is
already very high _ that's all to the good. And to the extent that
we can downgrade what some call the `Animal House' image, that
certainly is all to the good.''
   Freedman said his goals are traditional Dartmouth aspirations,
but the college cannot be static. For example, he said, ``It's
essential for Dartmouth to have foreign students here if our
students are going to be prepared for an international world.''
   In a March speech, Freedman showed his mettle _ and consolidated
the opposition _ when he publicly chastised the off-campus Dartmouth
Review, the contentious weekly founded in 1980 with the support of
such prominent conservatives as William F. Buckley and Patrick
Buchanan.
   The Review has been central to many campus controversies,
including the 1986 smashing of symbolic anti-apartheid shanties on
the college green.
   That incident inflamed an already polarized campus and provoked
demonstrations, arrests, a rare suspenion of classes for a
campuswide forum on racism, student takeovers of campus buildings
and a faculty vote of no-confidence in Freedman's predecessor as
president, David McLaughlin.
   Early this year, white Review staffers and a black music
professor clashed, again prompting cries of racism.
   After writing that Professor William Cole's course was ``one of
Dartmouth's most academically deficient,'' the student reporters
argued with Cole in a classroom while seeking his reaction. Three
were suspended for disrupting the class and harassing Cole, whom the
Review had earlier described as looking like ``a used Brillo pad.''
   Freedman's March speech to the faculty and news media denounced
Review reporters as ``ideological provocateurs posing as
journalists'' who engage ``in malicious bullying tactics'' that
threaten Dartmouth's commitment to diversity.
   ``There was a real need for the kinds of words he spoke to be
pronounced by somebody who had official leadership of the college,''
said David Sices, a 1945 graduate who has taught French and Italian
for 31 years at Dartmouth.
   Henry Eberhardt, director of the Alumni Fund for nine years,
agreed. ``Nobody had the guts to stand up and say that before him,''
he said. ``It was long overdue.''
   Van Deusen saw things differently.
   ``He's appeasing the faculty, just as simple as that,'' he said.
``He obviously wants to get one of the big constituencies of
Dartmouth on his side and he obviously did that.''
   Hart said Freedman turned an issue of ``academic quality and
civility and manners'' into ``a racial cliche.'' A Wall Street
Journal editorial said the incident illustrated discrimination
against conservatives on campus.
   The Review's lawyers have filed lawsuits alleging racial
discrimination, against whites, and free-speech violations.
   And conservative columnist James Kilpatrick wrote that Dartmouth
``has behaved shamefully. Only the most devoted friends of this
small college could love it now.''
   As the disputes persist, Freedman acknowledges his outsider's
view of Dartmouth makes his job tougher.
   ``But I do think it gives you a very great opportunity,'' he
said. ``You just see the place through fresh eyes.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Monday PMs, Nov. 7</NOTE>
</DOC>
