<1ST_LINE>a a PM-LouisianaInvestigator ADV09   11-03 0654</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Louisiana Investigator, ADV 09,0671</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv09</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Wednesday PMs, Nov. 9, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Reporter Trades Notepad For State Investigator's Job</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For more than two decades, Bill Lynch
tried as an investigative reporter to ferret out corruption in a
state where kickbacks and sweetheart deals were as much a part of
the culture as Mardi Gras and Cajun cooking.
   Shortly after Gov. Buddy Roemer took office in March, Lynch
traded his notepad and job with the New Orleans Times-Picayune for
the newly created post of state inspector general.
   His job may have changed, but his mission hasn't.
   ``We've never had an office before dedicated to the idea of
running state government in an honest manner, the way we can all be
proud of,'' Lynch said.
   His reputation as an investigative reporter was such that when
the Legislature passed a bill tacking on punitive damages to libel
judgments in the late 1970s, the statute became known as the ``Lynch
Law.'' The law was later repealed.
   Lynch, 59, is the chief investigator for a governor who
campaigned on the need to root out corruption in Louisiana _ a
legacy dating to the 1930s reign of Huey P. Long.
   Starting with Long's legendary ``deduct box'' containing money
extorted from state employees for his political purposes, political
history here has been checkered. The ``Louisiana Scandals'' of 1939
resulted in the imprisonment of former Gov. Dick Leche. In 1986,
former Gov. Edwin Edwards was acquitted of racketeering charges.
   ``Corruption in government has virtually been a way of life,''
said Lynch. ``The thing we want to do is to turn that around. Both
nationally and internationally, Louisiana has been looked upon with
disdain, contempt. We want to change that perception.
   ``But most importantly, we want to change the substance. We don't
want people just to perceive that we're honest people, honest
government. That's what Roemer asked me to do.''
   How does Roemer rate Lynch's performance so far? ``Excellent,''
the governor said.
   ``We inherited a mess and one person can't clean that up. A
governor can't do that alone,'' Roemer said. ``We thought during the
campaign and during the transition that the office of inspector
general with enough teeth, enough staff and enough independence to
check every agency one by one would be in the taxpayers' best
interest.
   ``I think Bill's done a terrific job. A number of small
suggestions and small savings and a number of big-picture
modifications.''
   For example:
   _ Lynch's investigation into the Louisiana Racing Commission,
which regulates the state's horse racing industry, revealed payroll
abuses and allegations that a commission telephone at Louisiana
Downs, the state's major track, was used to relay information to
bookmakers. Roemer replaced the entire commission.
   _ Lynch's office recommended the dismissal of the executive
director and the board of the Governor's Special Task Force On
Education, which handled federal grant programs for students at
vocational-technical schools. Some students had to drop out because
of delays in processing the grants, according to an inspector
general's report. Roemer is reviewing the report.
   _ Since a state official was investigated for using a government
telephone for private long-distance calls, the state's monthly
telephone bill has dropped by about $280,000 a month, the Roemer
administration says.
   _ Numerous violations of state travel regulations within agencies
that generate their own funds through fees were uncovered. Lynch's
office said members of the Real Estate Commission traveled at state
expense on a junket to Hawaii.
   Lynch's job is limited to the executive branch of government.
Twenty-two auditors work under him and he reports his findings
directly to the governor.
   ``The primary objective of this organization is to save money
through the honest operation of government,'' he said. ``Government
was not just put here for the personal (use) of the individual,
though you couldn't tell it from the past several decades.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Wed PMs, Nov. 9</NOTE>
</DOC>
