<1ST_LINE>a a PM-APonTV-SecondCity ADV04   11-03 0884</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-AP on TV-Second City, ADV 04,0908</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv04</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Fri PMs, Nov. 4, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>`Second City' Isn't Kidding This Time in Arty Showtime Special</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BARR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early in ``Second City's 15th Anniversary
Special,'' a promising, unknown character appears on the screen.
   ``I've laid a bunch of trips on actors at the Second City,'' says
this character, identified as ``Del Close, director.'' He wears a
hideous red shirt and waves a cigarette, his mouth turned down in
the relentless grimace of a society matron.
   ``And some of these they've been able to use and some they
haven't _ but I'm going to loop back to your previous question for a
second, because embedded in it is part of a question I didn't answer
...''
   Amazing! Who's doing this guy? Eugene Levy? Joe Flaherty? Martin
Short? Terrific makeup. It could even be Catherine O'Hara.
   But the realization comes that this is Del Close, director at
Second City in Toronto, and he really wants to talk about serious
dramaturgical issues. Improvisation _ boon or bane?
   Yes, Second City is getting serious on this hour-long Showtime
special, which appears Saturday at 10 p.m. EST. Repeat dates are
Nov. 8, 16, 21 and 27.
   Del is all for improv, a specialty of the Second City troupe. He
loves improv not as a method of developing material, but for itself.
   ``Like fireworks, the most ephemeral of art forms. Once it's
gone, (finger snap) it's gone, baby.''
   Then comes Bernard Sahlins, director, who thinks Del is, if not
all wet, a bit moist. For Bernard, improvisation is ``not a really
presentational form.''
   So you thought Second City did comedy, huh?
   Fortunately, most of the hour is devoted to laughs. Levy,
Flaherty, Short and O'Hara are all present, and so are Andrea
Martin, Dave Thomas and Robin Duke. There are also two very funny
guys who weren't part of the SCTV experience, John Hemphill who
appears as the gunsel Johnny Prolongo, and bald, nervous Don Lake,
who plays a very bad lounge singer with a yen for Peru.
   There's no rust on these clowns yet. However, there is just a
smidgen of self-congratulation in this special, as if the two Emmys,
a dozen Emmy nominations, all the Canadian awards and the critical
adulation has been taken too seriously.
   It shows in the montages of black-and-white photos of times past,
reminding the viewer that Dan Aykroyd and Gilda Radner were in the
original Toronto cast and that John Candy was later a star. The same
photos remind you that they aren't in the special.
   There is a feeling of dread that Barbra Streisand will begin
crooning ``The Way We Were'' at any moment.
   It never gets that far out of hand. Short, notably, can talk
about technique without being pompous.
   ``Stallone and I had the same approach toward improvisation,'' he
says. ``A few words, just impact with physical, fall down, hit a
wall, hair like that, go WAAA-HA-HA!''
   There are four skits in the show, each beginning with the stage
version and then intercutting to a much more polished version _ with
costumes, makeup and scenery _ done for the cameras.
   Short appears twice, as the old bore Brian Allen (``I'm Brian
Allen, and this is my wife, Mrs. Brian Allen'') and as Robespierre.
He's funny on stage, but hilarious on camera. His Robespierre on
stage isn't quite sure who he is, but on film Short adds a dazzling
series of smiles, simpers and eye flutters.
   Levy, appearing as a snooty French waiter in the Brian Allen
sketch, shows yet again why he has the best spectacle-and-eyebrow
act since Groucho Marx. Above the nose, Levy may be the funniest man
alive.
   Catherine O'Hara is divine, and Andrea Martin is wonderful, and
Thomas is funny, and isn't it awful that SCTV still isn't on the
air, even at 1 a.m. like it was when you had to sit through some of
the worst of the ``Saturday Night Live'' casts to catch the show on
NBC?
   But can't we just be happy that Short, Flaherty and O'Hara are
doing ``The Completely Mental Misadventures of Ed Grimley'' every
Saturday, and they're doing movies, and every once in a while
someone drags out an SCTV retrospective that gets lousy ratings and
means SCTV probably won't ever be back?
   Maybe Del Close has it right. Maybe SCTV, like fireworks, was the
most ephemeral of art forms. And ``once it's gone, baby, it's gone.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AND STARRING LLOYD BENTSEN AS THE BEAVER _ ``Dukakis for
President'' was a top-20 show in the weekly Nielsen rankings the
week ending Oct. 30. The five-minute paid-political spot aired at
the conclusion of the high-rated Geraldo Rivera and got a rating of
18.2 and a 27 share, good enough for 18th place and just ahead of
``Night Court.'' If Mike could pull say a 32 share, he might have a
shot at a series commitment from NBC. ...
   THE ABSOLUTELY POSITIVELY LAST AND FINAL WORD _ PBS will have a
live, two-hour special Nov. 7, election eve, ``Campaign: The Last
Word,'' a discuss-fest that will include Paul Duke, Robert MacNeil
and Jim Lehrer, Henry Hampton, Bill Moyers, Roger Mudd, Louis
Rukeyser and Judy Woodruff. ...
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri PMs, Nov. 4</NOTE>
