<1ST_LINE>a a AM-MigrantEducation ADV10   11-03 0776</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Migrant Education, ADV 10,0800</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Thurs AMs, Nov. 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Helping Migrant Students Succeed, Despite Rootless Life</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MALDEN, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Every year, schools in southern Missouri
welcome hundreds of children who are as rootless as the tufts of
cotton that drift with the autumn leaves through the streets of this
Bootheel town.
   The Southeast Missouri Migrant Education Center here, part of a
federal network that includes a southwest Missouri branch in Monett,
helps local schools bring some stability to the lives of the
children of the migrants _ who pick apples and melons, work in
cotton gins and poultry plants, moving with the seasons to make a
living.
   For Tracy Oldnette, a slight 12-year-old with a shy smile, the
program means a special relationship with Mary K. Scott, a migrant
education teacher in the Monett school system.
   Tracy has been enrolled in Monett schools three different times.
Each time he spent part of his school day with Mrs. Scott, who is
both friend and tutor to the migrant children with whom she has
worked for 17 years.
   ``When we need help, she's always there,'' Tracy said.
   He estimates with a vague shrug that he has attended six or seven
different schools as his family worked its way through Missouri and
Arkansas.
   As a migrant student, his school and health records are stored in
a central computer in Little Rock, Ark. Local centers can receive
copies of records in a matter of days after migrant students enroll
at a new school.
   The local centers also provide teaching supplies to the tutors
who work with migrant children. Staff nurses at the centers act as
health educators and oversee the funds used to help the children buy
glasses and meet other medical needs.
   ``We're the only program in the schools that can take care of
health needs. That's the strong point of our program,'' said Keith
Hill, director of the Malden center. ``It's hard to study and pay
attention if you've got a toothache.''
   The Missouri centers, serving about 1,000 with a combined budget
of roughly $500,000, are links in a national chain established by
Congress in 1966 to improve education for disadvantaged children.
   ``There's lots of programs to help special children,'' said Tony
Woodrum, director of the Monett center. ``This just happens to be
the one that helps children whose families move a lot.''
   The program stresses early childhood education and tries to help
migrants who have dropped out of school or who have taken longer
than average to obtain a high school diploma.
   To be eligible, a student must have moved within the past year so
that a parent or other family member could obtain seasonal work in
agriculture or fishing. A student can continue in the migrant
program for up to five years after his or her family has stopped
moving.
   The Monett center is installed in shopping center within sight of
Monett High School. The Malden center is housed in a converted
skating rink.
   Migrant teachers, some paid by the state or local school boards
and others paid by the federal government under the migrant
education program, work with children in small groups. They build
skills that were lost in the shuffle of moves.
   Younger children may be behind in reading or math skills; with
older children, teachers address more complicated problems.
   ``Through their movement, I know they're going to have a hard
time learning the necessary things about applying for a job, or
maybe not meet with a counselor enough for him to work with him on
selecting a career,'' Hill said.
   Hill and Woodrum said that as children grow older and insist on
staying with familiar friends and schools, parents are more likely
to abandon migrant work. The educators acknowledge, however, that
many older children simply drop out to work in the fields, perhaps
despairing of any chance to break the cycle.
   ``You see it coming,'' Mrs. Scott said, ``but what can you do to
hold it off?''
   She added, ``One of our goals is to improve their self-confidence
_ so that they don't feel bad that they don't have roots in a
community. We point out that there are good things about having
lived in so many places.
   ``We've had some students that came in in the middle school and
have graduated. I don't know whether I had anything to do with it or
not, but I feel good about it.''
   Some students grow determined not to follow in their parent's
wandering footsteps.
   Said 11-year-old J.R. Seelye, ``I want to go to college.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thurs AMs, Nov. 10</NOTE>
