<HEAD>Rep. Young, Bush Favored to Win Easy Victories</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Rep. Don Young was favored to
win a ninth term as Alaska's lone congressman Tuesday, and Vice
President George Bush was expected to capture the state's three
electoral votes.
   Young's Democratic challenger Peter Gruenstein, 41, a former
prosecutor from Anchorage, attacked the incumbent as beholden to
special interests. Young, 44, stressed his 16 years of experience in
Congress.
   Officials of both major parties expected Bush to win the
presidential contest easily. Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis'
support of some controls on handguns and his opposition to oil
exploration in the Alaska National Wildlife Refuge hurt his chances
with the oil-rich state's largely conservative voters.
   State Democratic Party chairman John Pugh conceded Bush was
favored, but said Dukakis was ``doing better than any Democratic
candidate in a long while'' in Alaska.
</TEXT>
