<HEAD>Colorado Presidential Close; 6 Congressional Seats Also At Stake</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ballot initiatives making English the ``official''
state language and requiring voter approval of all future tax
increases dominated the final weeks of the campaign, as the
presidential battle for Colorado's eight electoral votes headed down
to the wire.
   The official English measure appeared headed for passage, but the
tax amendment faltered in the face of strong opposition by public
officials.
   George Bush, bolstered by his son Neil's high profile as a Denver
oilman and by Colorado's solidly Republican voting history in
presidential races, led Democrat Michael Dukakis by big margins most
of the fall.
   But a Denver Post-NewsCenter 4 poll released Thursday showed Bush
ahead by only 47 percent to 43 percent, with Dukakis planning a
Sunday visit that could make the race a tossup.
   Colorado's three Democratic and three Republican congressional
incumbents appeared headed for re-election.
</TEXT>
