<HEAD>Republican Governor and Senator Favored to Win Re-Election</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Gov. Michael N. Castle was
considered a cinch for re-election and GOP Sen. William V. Roth Jr.
was favored to capture a fourth term despite a spirited challenge
from Democratic Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo.
   In the presidential race, Vice President George Bush was expected
to defeat Democrat Michael Dukakis easily and claim Delaware's three
electoral votes.
   The one bright spot for Democrats appeared to be the race for the
state's lone congressional seat, where Rep. Thomas R. Carper was
widely favored over Republican challenger James P. Krapf.
   Woo, the nation's highest-ranking elected official of Chinese
descent, narrowly won a Democratic primary in September, defeating
civic activist Samuel Beard by 71 votes.
   But the independent-minded Woo, who often bucked the Democratic
Party leadership, ran an underdog race against the popular Roth. A
poll Oct. 22-26 conducted by the Wilmington News-Journal showed Roth
supported by 59 percent of likely voters, compared to only 29
percent for Woo.
   The same poll showed Castle with 75 percent of the support,
compared to a mere 14 percent for Democratic candidate Jacob
Kreshtool.
