<HEAD>Dukakis Slightly Ahead of Bush in Campaign Kickoff State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis carried a narrow lead
over George Bush to the wire in Iowa, where their only competition
for statewide attention was a little-noticed effort to change the
way the two top state officials are elected.
   Because of the lack of major races and Iowa's first-in-the-nation
precinct caucuses last February, most eyes have been on the state's
eight electoral votes. Both Bush and Dukakis finished third in the
caucuses.
   Bush suffered from unpopular Reagan administration farm policies
and a Democratic edge in voter registration. But the Republican
rebounded, and the last poll published by the Des Moines Register in
early October showed Dukakis ahead 49-38 with 13 percent undecided
and a 3.1 percent margin of error.
   The election change being sought would allow the governor and
lieutenant governor to run as a team, instead of independently.
Since 1982, the two offices have been split between the parties,
leaving the lieutenant governor with little to do.
   Republicans were expected to continue their 4-2 edge over
Democrats in the state's U.S. House delegation.
</TEXT>
