<HEAD>Bush Favored in Home State of One-time GOP Rival Dole</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush counted on a lopsided Republican
advantage in voter registration to deliver him the seven electoral
votes in the home state of his one-time rival for the presidential
nomination, Sen. Bob Dole.
   Democrats, however, retained a slim hope right up to election day
that Michael Dukakis would somehow attract what once was a sizable
bloc of undecided voters to his side.
   Of the state's 1.12 million registered voters, 42 percent are
Republicans. 29 percent Democrats and another 29 percent
unaffiliated. Kansas has voted only twice for Democrats in modern
times _ Franklin Roosevelt over Alf Landon in 1936 and Lyndon
Johnson over Barry Goldwater in 1964.
   The state's three Republican and two Democratic House members all
were favored to win re-election.
</TEXT>
