<HEAD>Bush Leading in Heavily Democratic State</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush was expected to claim
Kentucky's nine electoral votes Tuesday, furthering the frustration
of Democrats who despite a 2-1 edge in registration have seen the
state go Republican in five of the last seven presidential elections.
   The only statewide contest to generate interest was a proposal to
lift the constitutional ban on a lottery.
   A poll by The Courier-Journal released Oct. 30 showed Bush with a
53-38 lead over Michael Dukakis. The race had been virtually a dead
heat in the newspaper's September poll.
   The Massachusetts governor was hurt by his liberal image in
Kentucky, especially on the issues of gun control and crime, while
Bush benefited from the popularity of President Reagan.
   All four Democrats and three Republicans in the state's House
delegation appeared headed for re-election.
