<HEAD>Bush Seen As Leader In Recession-Plagued Louisiana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite Louisiana's deep recession
brought on by the collapse of oil prices, voters appeared satisfied
enough with Republican policies to hand the state's 10 electoral
votes to George Bush on Tuesday.
   According to a late October poll conducted for the Gannett News
Service and several television stations, Bush was favored by 50
percent, Dukakis by 44 percent and 6 percent were undecided. The
poll had a margin of error of 3.5 percent.
   Seven of the state's eight congressional races were settled in
the Oct. 1 primary. Republican incumbent Clyde Holloway of the 8th
District faced a rematch of his 1986 runoff against Democrat Faye
Williams, who sought to become the first black elected to Congress
from the state since Reconstruction.
</TEXT>
