<HEAD>Democratic Sen. Mitchell Heading for Landslide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUGUSTA, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic Sen. George J. Mitchell appeared
headed for a landslide re-election victory Tuesday, and Vice
President George Bush, who maintains a Maine address at his
Kennebunkport summer home, was favored to pick up the state's four
electoral votes.
   Bush carried an advantage of about 10 percentage points in polls
over Democrat Michael Dukakis in a state that has voted Republican
in all but three presidential elections in the past century.
   The only independent poll taken this year showed Mitchell, who is
seeking his second full term in the Senate, with an 8-1 advantage in
October over Jasper S. Wyman, a former Democratic state legislator
turned Republican. Wyman, who heads the conservative Maine Christian
Civic League, stepped forward to challenge Mitchell after more
established GOP figures refused to take him on.
   Both congressional incumbents were expected to win re-election _
Democrat Joseph E. Brennan, a former two-term governor, and
Republican Olympia J. Snowe.
</TEXT>
