<HEAD>Dukakis Holds Slim Lead, Durenberger Favored Over Humphrey</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis carried a slim lead into
Tuesday's presidential election, but fellow Democrat Hubert H.
Humphrey III appeared to have fallen short in his bid to unseat
Republican Sen. Dave Durenberger.
   Minnesotans also were deciding whether to legalize a lottery.
   Dukakis led Republican George Bush 48-46 percent in a poll
conducted Oct. 11-17 as they battled for the 10 electoral votes
offered by Minnesota, the only state to elude Ronald Reagan in his
1984 re-election landslide.
   In the most recent Senate poll, Durenberger led Humphrey by a
53-42 percent margin.
   The two traded bitter accusations in an aggressive TV ad
campaign. Humphrey, son of the late senator and vice president,
claimed that Durenberger voted to increase defense spending at the
expense of Medicare and helped write legislation that forced rural
hospitals to close.
   Durenberger, first elected in November 1978, blamed his opponent
for an increase in violent crime that occurred since Humphrey became
attorney general in 1983.
   The state's five Democratic and three Republican congressmen were
favored to win re-election.
</TEXT>
