<HEAD>Dukakis Hopes For Victory Despite GOP Runaways in Senate, Governors
Races</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Republican Sen. John Danforth and Gov.
John Ashcroft appeared headed for landslide re-election victories
Tuesday, but Democrat Michael Dukakis held out hope of taking
Missouri's 11 electoral votes.
   Missourians will decide the fate of the so-called MedAssist
proposal, a $296 million tax increase to finance a statewide health
insurance plan. Critics said it would line the pockets of doctors
and hospitals; supporters said it would protect Missourians who
can't afford health care coverage.
   The presidential race between Dukakis and George Bush remained a
toss-up in this traditionally Democratic state. Recent polls showed
Ashcroft enjoying as much as a 35-point lead over challenger Betty
Hearnes, wife of a former governor. Danforth led state Sen. Jay
Nixon by as much as 51 points.
   Democrats now control five of nine U.S. House seats and all of
them _ including one-time presidential candidate Richard Gephardt _
were expected to win re-election.
   Republican Rep. Bill Emerson faced a tough rematch with
Democratic farm activist Wayne Cryts, who almost beat Emerson in
1986 in southeast Missouri's 8th District.
</TEXT>
