<HEAD>Close Governor's Race Tops Montana Ballot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HELENA, Mont. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hotly contested race for governor topped
Montana's ballot, as former Democratic Gov. Thomas Judge sought a
comeback and Republican Stan Stephens battled to reclaim the post
for his party for the first time in 20 years.
   Democratic Sen. John Melcher was favored to win a third term by
turning back a challenge from Republican Conrad Burns, a county
commissioner and relative newcomer to Montana politics.
   In the presidential race for Montana's four electoral votes,
polls showed Republican George Bush headed into the final week of
the campaign leading Democrat Michael Dukakis by 15 percentage
points.
   The race to succeed retiring Gov. Ted Schwinden was dominated by
debate over how to revive the state's economy. Stephens, a former
state senator, headed toward the election running even with Judge,
who served as governor from 1973-81, until Schwinden upset him in a
primary. A poll published in late October gave each candidate 41
percent of the vote.
