<HEAD>Bingaman Seems Assured of Re-election, Bush Leading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Jeff Bingaman, whom Republicans
have been calling vulnerable for the past two years, appeared
assured of re-election Tuesday, but fellow Democrat Michael Dukakis
was unlikely to share his victory.
   Bingaman has maintained a wide lead in media polls over his
Republican challenger, state Sen. Bill Valentine, 44, of
Albuquerque. A poll conducted Oct. 25-27 for the Albuquerque Journal
had 61.9 percent supporting Bingaman and 27.5 percent backing
Valentine. The margin of error was plus or minus 4 percentage points.
   Bingaman, 45, who ousted Republican first-term Sen. Harrison
Schmitt in 1982, worked hard to avoid the same fate by broadening
his political support and making inroads into conservative ranks.
   In the presidential race, New Mexicans appeared ready to give
their five electoral votes to Republican George Bush. The latest
Journal poll showed the vice president with 49.6 percent support to
37.8 percent for Dukakis.
