<NOTE>Eds: St Germain, no period, is cq</NOTE>
<DATELINE>PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Questions of ethics put Republican Gov.
Edward D. DiPrete and 14-term Democratic Rep. Fernand J. St Germain
in jeopardy as they sought re-election Tuesday.
   Democrat Michael Dukakis led Republican George Bush most of the
summer in the quest for Rhode Island's four electoral votes, but
late October polls gave conflicting readings on whether the
Massachusetts governor still led in his own back yard.
   Republican Sen. John H. Chafee appeared comfortably ahead in his
bid for a third term against Democratic Lt. Gov. Richard A. Licht.
   In the governor's race, Democrat Bruce G. Sundlun, a
communications executive who lost badly to DiPrete in 1986, took a
nine-point lead in polls. DiPrete, seeking a third term, was hurt by
allegations that he engaged in improper business dealings, showed
favoritism in the granting of state contracts and that his
administration hired a reputed mobster's ex-wife for a job on the
Governor's Justice Commission, then fired her two days later.
   St Germain, powerful chairman of the House Banking Committee,
faced Republican lawyer Ronald K. Machtley. The challenger tried to
capitalize on reports that the House Ethics Committee had not
finished its review of allegations that St Germain underreported his
assets by more than $1 million and accepted gifts from lobbyists.
   The state's other House member, Republican Rep. Claudine
Schneider, appeared assured of re-election.
