<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 1711EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-CampaignNarrative ADV06-4takes   11-03 1330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Narrative, ADV 06 - 4 takes,1379</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>Not Just a Presidential Election, but Choosing a Government</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans aren't just electing a president on Tuesday; they're
choosing a government and, in some cases, changing the rules.
   Ballots includes candidates for president, 33 Senate seats, 435
seats in the House of Representatives, 12 governors' offices, plus
state and local ballot issues and races for mayor, sheriff, state
legislatures and county officers.
   The voting traditionally begins just after midnight EST Tuesday
in Dixville Notch, N.H., where 38 registered voters will get their
moment of media attention by choosing between George Bush and
Michael Dukakis.
   And it ends 25 hours later _ long after the nation is likely to
know the name of its 41st president _ on the treeless, windy western
Aleutian Islands in Alaska.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ALABAMA (9 electoral votes)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush has a strong lead here, according to the latest University
of Alabama's Capstone Poll, which put the race at 57 percent Bush,
37 percent Dukakis.
   There are no races for governor or U.S. senator on what is a
short statewide ballot for Alabama.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ALASKA (3)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   GOP state chairman Jim Crawford has predicted Bush will win 60
percent of the vote. Dukakis' support of some controls on handguns
and his opposition to oil exploration in the Alaska National
Wildlife Refuge have been liabilities.
   Democrat Peter Gruenstein, 41, of Anchorage is challenging
veteran Republican Rep. Don Young, 55, a former river boat captain
from Fort Yukon, in the race for Alaska's only House seat.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ARIZONA (7)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush has a lopsided lead here in public opinion surveys.
   State Democratic chairman Sam Goddard said, however, that a
ballot proposal to make English Arizona's official language should
bring out large number of Hispanic voters in opposition, and ``if
they do come out they'll vote for Dukakis,'' he said. But state GOP
chairman Burton Kruglick contended, ``The don't vote.''
   In the Senate race, a poll published Oct. 26 by The Mesa Tribune
and KTSP-TV of Phoenix showed Democratic Sen. Dennis DeConcini
leading Republican challenger Keith Degreen 44 percent to 18 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ARKANSAS (6)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Bill Clinton, who made a memorably dull nominating speech
for Dukakis, has worked hard for the ticket at home and in other
states. However, the state still leans Republican and recent public
opinion surveys back that up.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CALIFORNIA (47)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   With the largest number of electoral votes at stake, California
has been a major campaign battleground. Bush trailed Dukakis by 16
percentage points in a late July poll but pulled ahead by as much as
11 points in one survey after the second debate on Oct. 13.
   ``The debate was the defining moment,'' pollster Mervin Field
said. The race remains close, however.
   Republican Sen. Pete Wilson has led his Democratic challenger,
Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy, throughout the race but the margin has
dwindled a bit in the closing days. McCarthy was able to raise only
about half as much as Wilson, who had $13 million for his
second-term campaign.
   More than $60 million has been spent by insurance, attorney and
consumer groups battling over five competing auto insurance ballot
propositions, and another $17 million has been spent in the campaign
on a cigarette tax initiative, and 20 other statewide ballot
propositions have generated another $15 million in campaign spending.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>COLORADO (8)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Denver Post-KCNC-TV poll on Oct. 31 showed Bush ahead 56
percent to 37 percent. The vice president made half a dozen trips to
the state, and son Neil, a Denver oilman, has been active in the
campaign.
   The dominant ballot issue appeared to be a tax limitation
proposal spearheaded by realtor David Bruce. It would bar any state
or local tax increase at the state or local unless it was approved
by two-thirds of the voters.
   Gov. Roy Romer strongly opposed the initiative, saying it would
hurt public education. ``Colorado will regret this,'' he said. Bruce
contended Romer was misleading the public, but the Post-KCNC poll
showed the initiative trailing by 50 percent to 41 percent.
   An initiative to make English the state's official language was
leading in the polls, while a vote about restoring state funding for
abortions was too close to call.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>CONNECTICUT (8)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gov. William A. O'Neill, a Democrat, has said that if Dukakis
can't win in Connecticut, he can't win the election. The most recent
polls indicated a close race, with Bush slightly ahead.
   Republican Sen. Lowell P. Weicker Jr., a nationally known
maverick, found himself in an unexpectedly tough race against state
attorney general Joseph I. Lieberman. Weicker expects to spend about
$2.8 million and Lieberman $2.5 million, a state record.
   Although polls indicate a dead heat, Weicker, who has survived
other cliffhangers, has run negative ads that may be working.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DELAWARE (3)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis' summer lead melted to an 11-point deficit in the latest
poll by The (Wilmington) News-Journal papers.
   Republican Gov. Michael N. Castle, leading opponent Jacob
Kershtool almost 7-to-1 in the News-Journal poll and even further
ahead in fund-raising, lent some of his staff to the Bush campaign.
   Despite a slight money advantage, Democratic Lt. Gov. S.B. Woo
trailed incumbent Sen. William V. Roth Jr. The News-Journal poll
showed Roth leading 51 percent to 29 percent.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DISTRICT of COLUMBIA (3)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis has a wide lead the district, which has supported the
Democrat in the last five presidential elections.
   Democrat Walter Fauntroy, the city's non-voting delegate to
Congress, has has token opposition to his bid for a tenth term.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FLORIDA (21)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Dukakis campaign wrote off Florida in early October and sent
campaign workers to more promising states, though Democrats claimed
that tracking polls showed Dukakis narrowing the gap from 25 percent
to 12 percent.
   Democrat Kenneth ``Buddy'' MacKay has taken pains in his Senate
campaign to distance himself from Dukakis on issues such as the
death penalty. Republican Rep. Connie Mack, grandson of the
legendary baseball owner and manager, has played up MacKay's
agreement with Dukakis on defense issues and on withdrawing support
from the Nicaraguan Contras. The Senate race remains a tossup.
   A referendum to make English the state's official language is
also on the ballot.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>GEORGIA (12)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   An Atlanta Journal-Constitution poll released in October showed
Bush leading Dukakis by 12 points throughout the Southeast, and
local pollster Claibourne Darden predicted Bush to take Georgia by
10 to 14 points.
   However, popular Sen. Sam Nunn has lately pitched in to help
Dukakis, and appeared with the candidate on the stump.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>HAWAII (4)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis considered the likely victor in a state with a long
Democratic tradition.
   The health of Sen. Spark Matsunaga, 72, has been an issue in his
campaign for a third term, but his 71-year-old Republican opponent,
Maria Hustace, has not raised it directly.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>IDAHO (4)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Democrats pessimistic. State party chairman Conley Ward recently
conceded Dukakis would do only slightly better than 40 percent of
Idaho vote, and Democratic Gov. Cecil Andrus, who is not up for
re-election, said the campaign could not end too soon for him.
   The state's hottest issue is a constitutional amendment allowing
a state lottery. Lottery opponents, lead by church officials from
various denominations, raised about $500,000, while pro-lottery
forces attracted less than $10,000. A similar measure was endorsed
3-2 in 1986, but later voided by the state supreme court.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>ILLINOIS (24)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   A key battleground state, and recent polls showed the
presidential race too close to call.
   Heavily Democratic Chicago is the wild card in the race, with the
outcome there seen as hinging in part on the number of supporters of
favorite son Jesse Jackson who turn out for Dukakis. One problem for
Democrats in Chicago is the divisions created in expectation of a
mayoral election next year.
   Some observers have suggested that the lack of statewide races
depressed interest in the election. Nearly 6.4 million people are
registered to vote, a drop of about 1.5 percent since 1984.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
