<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 1726EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>s p BC-CampaignNarrative ADV06-2ndAdd   11-03 1037</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Narrative, ADV 06 - 2nd Add,1071</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: point lead.</HEAD>
<HEAD>NORTH CAROLINA (13)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Republican leaders conceded that Bush was at least 10 points
behind this summer, but polls by the Charlotte Observer showed the
race even in mid-September and Bush with a double-digit lead late
last week.
   Republican Gov. Jim Martin, who is running for re-election, was
conspicuously absent when Bush appeared in Charlotte in July and
missed Quayle's early-October visit to Raleigh. However, Martin
later campaigned alongside Bush and Quayle.
   His Democratic opponent, Lt. Gov. Bob Jordan, stood by the
Dukakis-Bentsen ticket but mentioned it less as Bush's lead widened.
Jordan derisively labeled Martin ``the sitting governor,'' and used
four chimpanzees in one television commercial that lampooned
Martin's budget staff.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>NORTH DAKOTA (3)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Democrats expect to sweep nearly every statewide office but lose
the presidential race.
   Despite his age (80) and a recent operation, Sen. Quentin Burdick
has maintained a large lead in University of North Dakota polls over
Republican Earl Strinden, the longtime majority leader in the state
House.
   Rep. Byron Dorgan seemed headed for another landslide in the race
for the state's lone House seat. Republican Steve Sydness was
outspent 12-1 and hasn't broken 20 percent in polls.
   First-term Gov. George Sinner, who pushed through the state's
largest tax increase last year, also had a big lead over Republican
Leon Mallberg.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OHIO (23)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   One of the key states of the 1988 presidential election, Ohio may
be the Republican's strongest state in the industrial Midwest, with
Bush visiting often in recent weeks in an effort to blunt a Dukakis
comeback.
   In Ohio's U.S. Senate election, polls showed Democratic incumbent
Howard Metzenbaum leading by 25 percent and more in late October.
Republican George Voinovich, the mayor of Cleveland, ran widely
criticized ads that portrayed Metzenbaum as soft on child
pornography and never seemed to mount the expected challenge.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OKLAHOMA (8)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   After starting even on Labor Day, Bush pulled out to a 58 percent
to 36 percent lead in a late October poll conducted by pollster
Thomas Kielhorn. However, Kielhorn said one out of four voters were
still ``available for persuasion,'' which more than a fourth of
Bush's supporters were disaffected Democrats who might vote at all.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>OREGON (7)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush got a chilly reception when he made a ``good times'' speech
to unionized shipyard workers in the state and Oregon shaped up as a
state where Dukakis could be aided by environmental sentiment.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>PENNSYLVANIA (25)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Another state Dukakis counted on winning, but now a tossup which
drew a hastily arranged Bush visit two Sundays before Election Day.
   Gov. Robert P. Casey, a conservative Democrat who narrowly won in
1986, complains the national party is too liberal but has
nonetheless appeared several times with Dukakis. Generating
enthusiasm among black voters in Philadelphia is a key to Dukakis'
chances.
   Sen. John Heinz is a prohibitive favorite against Democrat Joseph
Vignola, a former Philadelphia city controller. Vignola has been
unable to raise more than $500,000 for the entire campaign while
Heinz, an heir to the pickle and catsup fortune, raised millions and
has been running ads for months.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>RHODE ISLAND (4)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The presidential campaign has been overshadowed by a bitter
gubernatorial race between incumbent Republican Edward DiPrete and
Democrat Bruce G. Sundlun. Sundlun, who lost in a landslide two
years ago, struck back with stories about DiPrete family land deals,
state contracts awarded to contributors and the hiring of an ex-wife
of a reputed mobster for the staff of the Governor's Justice
Commission. Sundlun, a multimillionaire communications executive,
was spending more than $1 million of his own money.
   Polls a week before the election showed Sundlun 9 percentage
points ahead of DiPrete, with a 5-point margin of error.
   Rep. Fernand St Germain has been fighting off ethics allegations.
   Republican Sen. John Chafee, seeking a third term, held a wide
lead over Lt. Gov. Richard Licht.
   Victory in Rhode Island, with just four electoral votes, would do
little for Dukakis, but defeat in this neighboring state would be an
embarrassment. The Democrat's early advantage appears to have slid,
but some Republicans privately expect him to win.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTH CAROLINA (8)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush has led consistently since defeating Bob Dole and Pat
Robertson in the state's key March primary. Campaign manager Lee
Atwater hails from South Carolina, the governor is active on Bush's
behalf and the state enjoys a decided influence with Bush.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>SOUTH DAKOTA (3)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Republican and Democratic officials have said in the past few
months that the presidential race is very close in this farm state,
and a public opinion poll released Oct. 21 by the University of Iowa
Social Science Institute rated South Dakota as a tossup.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TENNESSEE (11)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The Democratic governor said not too long ago that he thought
Bush was leading, but held out hope for a Dukakis upset. Dukakis'
campaign schedule suggested he might be more confident about
next-door Kentucky.
   Sen. James Sasser, a Democrat, was heavily favored to win a third
term. His Republican opponent, Bill Andersen, is a law partner of
former White House chief of staff and senator Howard Baker.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>TEXAS (29)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Perhaps the pivotal state in the presidential race. Despite
economic problems caused by the oil industry's collapse and Lloyd
Bentsen on the Democratic ticket, Bush led in his adopted state
going into the final days with a margin that had not dipped below 6
or 7 percent.
   In his separate Senate race (allowed under the 1959 ``Lyndon
Law'' passed for Lyndon Johnson), Bentsen had raised nearly $8.5
million and was expected to drub two-term Rep. Beau Boulter.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>UTAH (5)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush was sure to win the presidential race, but first-term
Republican Gov. Norm Bangerter is in trouble after pushing a record
$166 million tax increase through the Legislature. Democratic former
Salt Lake City Mayor Ted Wilson led Bangerter 40-32 in a three-way
race. Republican-turned-independent Merrill Cook was supported by 26
percent.
   Among the three, Cook alone supports tax-cutting initiatives
which would shrink state and local revenues by $300 million.
   Republican Sen. Orrin Hatch, who has been pressing for Cook to
get out of the race, was expected to defeat Democrat Brian Moss.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
