<1ST_LINE>s p BC-CampaignNarrative ADV06-3rdAdd   11-03 0726</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Campaign Narrative, ADV 06 - 3rd Add,0746</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For release Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>UNDATED: Brian Moss.</HEAD>
<HEAD>VERMONT (3)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Madeleine Kunin, seeking a third term, was thought to enjoy
a comfortable lead over Republican challenger Michael Bernhardt, the
GOP leader in the Vermont House. The governor campaigned actively
for Dukakis, but Bush is believed to have a slight edge.
   In the Senate race, Republican Rep. James Jeffords is likely to
win the seat of retiring Republican Sen. Robert Stafford. William
Gray, a former U.S. Attorney for Vermont, is seeking to become only
the second Democrat to win a Senate seat from the state since the
Civil War.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>VIRGINIA (12)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Democrats are more likely to pick up a Republican Senate seat
here than in any other state. Charles S. Robb was far ahead of
retired black minister Maurice Dawkins in the race to succeed Sen.
Paul S. Trible Jr.
   Dukakis' state campaign director was sent to Pennsylvania several
weeks ago. Bush was leading by a 2-1 margin in an Oct. 21 university
poll.
   Robb, who raised $2.9 million to his opponent's $200,000, appears
to have survived published reports that while he was governor he
attended parties where cocaine was used. Robb denied seeing any drug
use.
   The Democrat, son-in-law of Lyndon Johnson, has said he is
willing to raise taxes to keep spending under control, and has
parted company with Dukakis on the need to build two new aircraft
carriers, which would be built in Virginia.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON (10)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The presidential race is a tossup. A recent poll staked Bush to a
slight lead, but one Bush campaigner said he privately expects
Dukakis will win.
   In one of the most closely watched Senate races, liberal
Democratic Rep. Mike Lowry has shaved off his beard, toned down his
flamboyant style and caught up with former Sen. Slade Gorton, who
lost re-election two years ago. Incumbent Republican Dan Evans was
appointed after the death of Henry J. Jackson and chose not to run
for a second term.
   Democratic Gov. Booth Gardner is expected to win re-election
easily over evangelical conservative state Rep. Bob Williams.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WEST VIRGINIA (6)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Arch Moore, 65, a Republican seeking a fourth term, has been
gaining ground but still trailed by 16 points in a poll against
millionaire insurance executive Gaston Caperton.
   Caperton, 48, making his first run for political office, said
Moore has mismanaged state government, which has been unable to pay
its bills without borrowing from investment funds. Moore, who
repeatedly called Caperton ``young man'' during their only debate,
says his opponent is inexperienced and his insurance company poorly
managed.
   Senate Majority Leader Robert C. Byrd, seeking his sixth straight
term, has more or less ignored his Republican challenger, state Sen.
Jay Wolfe. Last week, the national Republican Senatorial Committee
told Wolfe to stop running a television commercial showing a bloody
fetus next to a photo of Byrd.
   A likely victory here for Dukakis, but no sure thing. Hard times
in the coal and steel industries, a high unemployment rate and a
2-to-1 Democratic lead in voter registration have cushioned Dukakis
from a Bush surge.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WISCONSIN (11)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Dukakis' double-digit lead of August has evaporated into a close
race, but some Republicans said they expect the Democrat to prevail.
A survey by The Milwaukee Journal showed Dukakis with a 2 percent
lead _ half the margin of error _ on Oct. 14-18.
   The other big state race pits millionaire businessman Herbert
Kohl, a Democrat, against state Sen. Susan Engeleiter for the seat
held for 31 years by Democrat William Proxmire. Kohl, 53, who is
making his first bid for public office, outspent Engeleiter $5.4
million to $1.9 million from Jan. 1-Oct.19.
   Kohl led Engeleiter by more than 15 points in a mid-October poll,
but the race has tightened considerably and Engeleiter won a
Milwaukee Journal endorsement based in part in the paper's
preference to see an increase in the number of women in the Senate.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WYOMING (3)</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Bush expected to win this traditionally Republican state.
   Sen. Malcolm Wallop, who has portrayed his race against
Democratic state Sen. John Vinich as a referendum on conservatism
vs. liberalism, led in a September poll.
   Republican Dick Cheney, President Ford's chief of staff, was
expected to easily win a sixth term in the House.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Advance for Sunday, Nov. 6</NOTE>
