<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   11-03 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0552</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British publishing magnate Robert Maxwell has
claimed victory in his $2.51 billion battle to acquire Macmillan
Inc. after a key court decision in Delaware.
   The Delaware Supreme Court essentially blocked the second of two
crucial Macmillan takeover defenses on Wednesday, just weeks after a
lower court knocked out the first defense.
   Both Maxwell and rival bidder Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. have
outstanding tender offers that expire at 12:01 a.m. Friday. But
experts say Maxwell is virtually guaranteed to win because his
all-cash $90.25 bid is higher than Kohlberg Kravis' $90.05
cash-and-securities offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   RJR Nabisco Inc. directors have tried to open up
the bidding for the giant consumer products company by issuing a
statement saying they are interested in reviewing acquisition
proposals.
   Wednesday's announcement came more than a week after Kohlberg
Kravis Roberts & Co. launched an unprecedented $20.3 billion tender
offer for Nabisco amounting to $90 a share.
   Market observers have said it was unlikely that a higher offer
would emerge. But Nabisco executives and their primary financial
partner, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., were believed to be working on
a counter-proposal.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WEST POINT, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Textile giant West Point-Pepperell Inc.
says its board has rejected as inadequate a $1.4 billion takeover
bid by the Chicago-based Farley Inc.
   Pepperell President Don Keller said Wednesday the board believed
the company should remain independent.
   Farley Chairman William F. Farley said in a statement he was
disappointed and believed his tender offer of $48 per share in cash
is a fair and full one.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury has indicted two small
brokerage firms and three investment professionals, including a
researcher for Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc., on charges of insider
trading and other fraud.
   The multiple-count indictment announced Wednesday by the
Manhattan U.S. attorney's office sharply expanded the roster of
people and companies implicated in the government's nearly
three-year-old crackdown on Wall Street corruption.
   It also cast a new cloud over Drexel, which is fighting
additional civil fraud charges by the Securities and Exchange
Commission and is the target of a separate grand jury investigation
stemming from Drexel's relationship with Ivan F. Boesky, the
imprisoned insider trader who has turned state's evidence.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's largest medical association is trying
to halt distribution of a ``smokeless cigarette,'' saying it should
be removed from shelves until it is judged ``safe for human
consumption.''
   The American Medical Association filed legal petitions Wednesday
with state health authorities in Arizona and Missouri, where the
product is being test marketed.
   Reynolds responded that its new product is ``a cigarette...not a
drug-delivery system, as the AMA has alleged.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the securities fraud trial of
the Washington Public Power Supply System's $2.25 billion bond
default has told the jury not to draw conclusions from out-of-court
settlements in the case.
   U.S. District Judge William Browning said the settlements didn't
indicate the guilt or innocence of the remaining parties.
   The trial resumed Wednesday after a five-day recess and following
settlement reached Monday with 14 utility companies.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>MORE</NOTE>
</DOC>
