<DOCNO> AP881103-0270 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 0116EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 1stAdd   11-03 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st Add,0506</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's productivity rose by an annual
rate of 1.3 percent from July through September, reversing a
second-quarter decline when new employment outpaced increases in
goods and services, the government reports.
   But on an annual basis, productivity improved only 0.8 percent,
the Labor Department said Wednesday, suggesting that the long-term
trend is for continued weakness in productivity.
   Analysts cautioned that continued weakness in productivity growth
offers little hope for lifting Americans' standard of living or
increasing U.S. competitiveness overseas.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes fell 7.8 percent in
September, the biggest decline in 16 months, according to the
Commerce Department.
   But the median price of new homes sold in September rose 8.1
percent from August to $118,000, from $110,000, the department said
Wednesday. The median price means half the homes sold for more and
half for less.
   Economists said the statistic provided further evidence that the
economy slowed during the third quarter of the year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fixed mortgage rates are at their lowest level
since the spring, but economists warn that the low rates won't last.
   A recently completed survey of 2,000 lenders by HSH Associates of
Butler, N.J., found that about 150 mortgage bankers and thrifts
offered rates of between 9.75 percent and 9.875 percent last week.
The average rate was 10.32 percent, HSH said.
   But market experts said Wednesday that continuing problems with
the dollar and some increase in inflation could pressure interest
rates and force them up to 11 percent by early 1989.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders to U.S. factories for manufactured goods
dropped 1.9 percent in September, reflecting a steep decline in
aircraft orders, the government reports.
   The Commerce Department said Wednesday that orders for durable
and non-durable goods dropped to $222.6 billion in September, $4.4
billion below the August level.
   The August decline followed a pattern set over the last several
months in which the presence or absence of big aircraft orders
greatly influenced the overall performance.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Supreme Court is confronting drug testing
in the American workplace for the first time.
   The High Court was urged by Attorney General Dick Thornburgh and
his top courtroom lawyer on Wednesday to uphold mandatory tests for
many railroad and Customs Service employees.
   The importance attached to the pair of cases by the
administration was underscored by Thornburgh's participation,
marking the first time that an attorney general appeared before the
high court since President Reagan took office.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell to a six-month low against the Japanese yen
Wednesday despite reported efforts by U.S. and Japanese central
banks to support the currency.
   The stock market finished mixed. The Dow Jones average of 30
industrials rose 5.87 points to 2,156.83.
   Bond prices declined.
   Gold and other precious metals prices soared. Energy futures
prices rose.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
