<DOCNO> AP881103-0271 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 0123EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-EconomyRdp     11-03 0384</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Productivity on the Rise Despite Bad Second Quarter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Government reports showing a decline in home sales and factory
orders and an anemic boost in productivity gave fresh evidence of a
slowdown in the nation's economy, economists said.
   Wednesday's productivity report by the Labor Department indicated
productivity rose by an annual rate of 1.3 percent from July through
September, reversing a second-quarter decline.
   But analysts said the recent trend of paltry growth in
productivity offered little hope for lifting Americans' standard of
living or increasing U.S. competitiveness.
   Revised figures indicated productivity dropped 2.4 percent in the
second quarter _ much worse than the 1.4 percent decline estimated
previously.
   ``Despite the strong growth of the economy over the past year,
there's still no significant change in a the weak trend in
productivity that we've seen since 1973,'' said Larry Chimerine,
chairman of the Wefa Group, a Bala Cynwyd, Pa., economic consulting
firm.
   ``Productivity growth averaging 1 percent a year remains this
country's major economic problem,'' he said.
   A Commerce Department report showed orders to U.S. factories
dropped 1.9 percent, or by $4.4 billion in September after rising by
3.2 percent in August.
   Orders for non-defense capital goods, a key indicator of business
investment plans, fell by 10 percent to $34.9 billion for the month.
   Another Commerce Department report showed new home sales fell a
dramatic 7.8 percent in September _ the biggest decline in 16 months
_ to seasonally adjusted annual rate of 659,000 units.
   The reports had little impact on the stock market, which finished
mixed in seesaw trading. The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials
rose 5.87 points to 2,156.83.
   Traders seemed more worried by a continuing slide in the dollar,
which dropped to a six-month low against the Japanese yen and
five-month lows against other major currencies.
   Dollar purchases by the Bank of Japan and the Federal Reserve,
aimed at propping up the currency, were only partially successful
because market participants felt the central banks were trying to
slow the U.S. currency's fall, not arrest it.
   Gold prices shot upward, partly in response to the dollar's
decline. Republic National Bank of New York said gold bullion was
bid at $420.90 a troy ounce as of 4 p.m. EST, up from $411.30 an
ounce late Tuesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881103-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 0124EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     11-03 0215</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0225</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Technical buying has pushed oil futures prices
higher again on the New York Mercantile Exchange.
   The December contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
U.S. crude, rose 31 cents Wednesday to close at $13.75 per barrel.
On Tuesday, the December contract slipped 14 cents.
   Prices for refined products traded on the exchange also advanced.
   The December contract for wholesale heating oil rose 0.18 cent a
gallon to settle at 43.35 cents, while the December contract for
unleaded gasoline rose 0.17 cent to 43.79 cents a gallon.
   Andrew Lebow, a trader with E.D.&F. Man International Futures
Inc., said crude oil prices improved in response to an American
Petroleum Institute report that stocks of crude had declined.
   A Wall Street Journal story that crude production by the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries jumped to 23 million
barrels a day last week had no effect on trading, Lebow said.
   In recent weeks, reports of stepped-up production by the
13-nation cartel has depressed prices, and traders were surprised
that Wednesday's story did not send prices lower.
   ``I think people really don't know what's fundamentally going
on,'' Lebow said.
   He attributed Wednesday's price movements mainly to technical
factors, but said strong demand helped push gasoline and heating
prices higher.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
