<1ST_LINE>r f PM-GizmoDay Bjt   11-03 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gizmo Day, Bjt,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inventors Get in the Front Door of The Sharper Image</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX3</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICH CARTIERE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Auto mechanic Ben DeRosier and his wife
Doris sat in the lobby of The Sharper Image's corporate office,
waiting to convince a product buyer their electric fingernail file
is a retailer's dream come true.
   ``I work in an office where all the girls are into long
nails...and after using this the nails are so smooth you can run
them down your stockings without causing even the tiniest snag,
something I'd never do after the beauty parlor,'' Doris DeRosier
said Wednesday.
   The couple were among the small crowd of inventors who every
month, gizmos in hand, get their foot in the door of the high-tech
gadget purveyor in hopes of getting their product into the company's
mail-order catalog.
   In search of unique merchandise, The Sharper Image for two years
has held open house on the first Wednesday of every month. About 35
inventors a month come from across the country to attend, including
some manufacturers offering exclusive rights to their products.
   About one in 50 products are taken under consideration. So far,
three open house items have made it into the company's 63 stores and
into its 2.5 million monthly catalogs.
   Devices rejected include a vacuum cleaner attachment that cuts
hair by sucking it into the hose and chopping it off at a pre-set
length; rotating sheets of wallpaper; and the ``Beauty Pillow,''
with a hole cut for the face in order to eliminate wrinkles.
   But there have been successes. Coming later this fall is the
BugVac _ the brainchild of Larry Volle, of Roseville _ a miniature
vacuum cleaner that ends the messy task of cleaning up dead pests.
   And a big hit has been the ``ShowerTek,'' a shaving mirror that
doesn't fog up in the bathroom. nearly 70,000 have been sold since
its inventor brought it in last year.
   The ShowerTek, now one of The Sharper Image's best-selling
products, was pooh-poohed by company president Richard Thalheimer _
until he took it home and tried it himself. Hot water circulating
from the shower head to behind the mirror keeps it fog free.
   While many inventors struggle for years to get an audience with
major manufacturers, Sharper Image decided to cut through the
bureaucracy.
   ``This represents the good old American dream, that if you've got
something you really believe in, you can come in and make your
pitch,'' said Doris DeRosier.
   The Sharper Image, which had sales of $160 million last year, is
known for innovation in both marketing and the selection of gifts.
Some of the more unusual ones include a $1,600 programmable home
robot, talking bathroom scales, suits of armor and even a $2,000
remote-controlled toy helicopter.
   The business was started in 1977 by then-attorney Thalheimer, who
started out selling digital stopwatches through the mail with ads in
running magazines.
   The company went public in April 1987. But Thalheimer, 40, runs
it much like a family firm, reserving for himself the final say on
all products.
   Among the new ideas he's got to decide on are battery-powered,
blinking earrings in the shapes of circles, triangles and squares,
designed by David LeBlanc of Atlantis Productions of Santa Rosa.
   As for the DeRosiers, The Sharper Image told them it would
consider carrying their electric fingernail file if they find a
manufacturer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP881103-0277 </DOCNO>
