<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     11-03 0330</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0344</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Still Rising</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar was lower against most major
currencies in European trading this morning but psychological
support and an absence of economic news checked continued selling
pressure.
   Gold prices continued to rise, benefiting from a rally on
platinum triggered by tight supplies.
   Foreign exchange dealers said early trading was thin and nervous.
They said the failure this week of several rounds of interventions
by the Bank of Japan and the U.S. Federal Reserve to push the dollar
higher had created selling pressure.
   But later in the morning, the dollar was holding steady,
supported by psychological factors and an absence of major economic
indicators, they said.
   Market players generally expect the dollar to trade within a
narrow range until after the U.S. presidential elections next
Tuesday.
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.7802 to buy one pound, more expensive for buyers than $1.7740
late Wednesday.
   Other mid-morning dollar rates compared with Wednesday's late
rates, included: 1.7725 West German marks, down from 1.7840; 1.4882
Swiss francs, down from 1.4975; 6.0160 French francs, down from
6.0885; 1.9984 Dutch guilders, down from 2.0193; 1,318.00 Italian
lire, down from 1,322.00; and 1.2235 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2275.
   In Tokyo, banks and financial markets were closed due to a
national holiday. In London, the dollar was trading at 124.45 yen,
down from the dollar's closing of 124.68 yen in Tokyo on Wednesday.
   In London, gold opened at a bid price of $420.50, up from
Wednesday's late bid price of $417.20 a troy ounce. London's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended gold price of $422.90 a
troy ounce at midmorning.
   In Zurich, it rose to $422.90 bid from $417 bid late Wednesday.
   Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at a bid $422.99, up from
$413.90 bid at Wednesday's close.
   Silver bullion was trading in London at a bid price of $6.51 a
troy ounce, up from $6.45 bid late Wednesday.
</TEXT>
