<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Pillsbury     11-03 0408</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Pillsbury,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pillsbury Board To Meet Today; Judge Allows Class Action Suit</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lead prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pillsbury Co.'s board of directors was
scheduled to meet today, but officials at the food and restaurant
company refused to say whether the board would announce a plan to
defend against the $5.23 billion takeover bid from Britain's Grand
Metropolitan PLC.
   Pillsbury's directors have already rejected the $60-a-share offer
and Chairman Philip Smith said shareholders would be informed of an
alternative before the tender offer expires on Tuesday.
   Pillsbury spokesman Larry Haeg would not disclose the time and
location of the regularly scheduled meeting. He said Pillsbury
officials have not met with Grand Met to discuss the offer.
   A group of dissident shareholders is suing Pillsbury to force the
company to negotiate the offer or come up with an alternative of
equal or greater value.
   Hennepin County District Court Judge Thomas Carey on Wednesday
granted a request by the dissident group that all shareholders be
represented as a class in the lawsuit.
   The class of Pillsbury shareholders in the lawsuit includes all
those who owned the stock before Oct. 17, the date Pillsbury's
directors rejected the tender offer. Over objections from Pillsbury,
Carey excluded Grand Met from the shareholder's group although the
company owned Pillsbury stock as early as August.
   Had Grand Met been included in the class, it would have been
enjoined from taking legal action against Pillsbury in other states.
   Steven Rothschild, a lawyer for Pillsbury, asked for Grand Met to
be included in the class to prevent the British conglomerate from
``getting two bites at winning.''
   ``Don't subject us to the multiple hits they are trying to
inflict on us,'' Rothschild said in court.
   But Carey said Grand Met has interests that are different than
the interests of shareholders.
   Carey also denied a request from Pillsbury that the shareholders'
lawsuit be dismissed.
   Similar legal action is pending in Delaware, where Pillsbury is
incorporated.
   In a suit separate from the shareholders' action, Pillsbury has
asked Carey to block the tender offer on grounds the proposed
takeover would violate state laws that forbid liquor distillers from
selling alcohol at retail outlets.
   Grand Met makes a variety of alcoholic beverages including J&B
Scotch. Pillsbury sells liquor at its Steak & Ale and Bennigan's
restaurants.
   Pillsbury stock closed Wednesday at $61.50, up 25 cents a share
in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
