<DOCNO> AP881103-0280 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 0927EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Macmillan 1stLd-Writethru   11-03 0563</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Macmillan, 1st Ld-Writethru,0583</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Maxwell Claims Victory In Battle For Macmillan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites thruout with Kohlberg Kravis merger invalidated. No
pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   British publisher Robert Maxwell has emerged the
apparent victor in the takeover battle for Macmillan Inc. after a
Delaware court invalidated Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co.'s merger
pact with the publishing and infomation services company.
   In a ruling Wednesday, a three-judge panel of the Delaware
Supreme Court reversed a Delaware Chancery Court judgment that last
month affirmed the $2.5 billion agreement between Macmillan and
Kohlberg Kravis.
   Maxwell is offering $2.51 billion for Macmillan.
   The court also ordered the lower court to issue a preliminary
injunction against a merger with Kohlberg Kravis. The ruling came
two weeks after Mcamillan lost a separate court challenge to its
``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense.
   At issue Wednesday was a so-called ``lock-up'' provision in the
Kohlberg Kravis deal that had given the powerful New York buyout
firm the right to buy certain prize Macmillan assets for $865
million if the publishing and information company is acquired by
another suitor.
   The provision, which was put in place in September, was intended
to discourage rival suitors, such as Maxwell, who likely would be
unwilling to buy Macmillan without those choice properties.
   Maxwell had contended that the lock-up, which covered Macmillan's
Berlitz language centers, the directory division, the direct
marketing division and a division that publishes state legal codes,
was unfair and would leave the company with a $250 million tax
liability.
   ``I am delighted by the court's decision which should clear the
way for our acquisition of Macmillan,'' Maxwell said in a statement
after the ruling.
   He also stated he had met with Macmillan Chairman Edward P. Evans
and other members of the management team on Wednesday. ``(I) am
pleased by their willingness to cooperate with me in ensuring an
orderly transition,'' he said.
   Spokesmen for Kohlberg Kravis, which also is making an
unprecedented $20.3 billion bid for RJR Nabisco Inc., were
unavailable for comment after the ruling.
   Both Maxwell and Kohlberg Kravis have outstanding tender offers
that expire at 12:01 a.m. Friday for Macmillan's 27.8 million
outstanding shares.
   Experts say Maxwell virtually is guaranteed to win a bidding
contest because his all-cash $90.25 a share bid is higher than the
$90.05 a share cash-and-securities offer from Kohlberg Kravis, which
has been endorsed by Macmillan.
   In trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Macmillan jumped $1.25
to $89.50 a share on Wednesday.
   The state supreme court decision came after a 2{-hour hearing in
which attorneys for Maxwell Communication Corp. PLC also argued that
Macmillan tainted the bidding process by revealing Maxwell's bid to
Kohlberg Kravis while withholding information on the offer from its
own board.
   Justice Andrew G.T. Moore II described Macmillan management's
defense against charges of improper bidding as sounding ``like
something I have read in Lewis Carroll,'' author of ``Alice in
Wonderland.''
   ``The process was tainted ... (because) information to the
(Macmillan) board was not accurate or complete ... it was misleading
in lack of candor,'' said Moore.
   Earlier this month, Assistant Chancellor Jack B. Jacobs issued a
injunction Oct. 17 prohibiting Macmillan's poison-pill defense, in
which Macmillan would have diluted the value of its stock.
   After that ruling, Maxwell appealed to the higher court to obtain
a court order against Macmillan's other dealings with Kohlberg
Kravis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
