<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 1000EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-SouthKorea-Trade     11-03 0259</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-South Korea-Trade,0268</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Trade Surplus With U.S. Shrinks;, Deficit With Japan Narrows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   South Korea's trade surplus with the
United States in the first nine months of this year declined 13.2
percent from a year ago, while its trade deficit with Japan fell 30
percent, the Korea Foreign Trade Association reported Thursday.
   The association said, however, that Korea's trade surplus with
the European Economic Community increased 16.6 percent during the
January-September period.
   The shifts in Korea's trade patterns with the United States and
Japan were attributed partly to its policy of buying more American
goods at the sacrifice of some of its imports from Japan.
   Under the policy designed to ease trade friction with America,
Seoul has eased its import restrictions on some American products
and somewhat revalued the Korean won currency against the dollar.
   Officials said Korea's trade surplus with the United States in
the nine months shrank 13.2 percent to $6.01 billion from $6.92
billion a year earlier.
   Korea's global trade surplus was $5.13 billion on exports of
$42.95 billion and imports of $37.82 billion, according to an
earlier government report.
   Korean exports to the United States were listed at $15.15
billion, up 14.3 percent from a year ago, and imports from the
United States were $9.14 billion, up 44.3 percent.
   Korea ran a deficit of $2.95 billion with Japan in the nine
months, down 30 percent from a year ago. Korean exports to Japan
jumped 48.6 percent to $8.54 billion and its imports from Japan grew
15.4 percent to $11.49 billion.
</TEXT>
