<1ST_LINE>u f PM-HollyFarms     11-03 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Holly Farms,0190</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Holly Farms Rejects Tyson Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officers of Holly Farms Corp. urged the
company's stockholders today to reject a roughly $940 million buyout
offer from rival poultry processor Tyson Foods Inc. of Springdale,
Ark.
   ``The offer is inadequate and not in the best interests of the
company and its stockholders,'' Holly Farms' board of directors said
in a statement.
   Tyson, the nation's largest poultry processor, is offering $52 a
share in cash for Holly Farms. The board of Holly Farms last month
rejected a previous Tyson offer, which consisted of $45 a share plus
a quarter share of Tyson stock for each of Holly Farms' 1.8 million
shares of Class A common stock.
   ``The board has authorized management together with the company's
financial and legal advisers to continue to explore alternatives to
Tyson Foods' offer in order to maximize value of the company's
stockholders,'' Holly Farms said.
   Holly Farms, based in Memphis, is a diversified food company with
about 50 percent of its sales in chicken. Tyson Foods produces 14
million pounds of chicken meat a week.
</TEXT>
