<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmScene 1stLd-Writethru f0017 11-03 0822</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0017,0842</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lyng Says He'll Stay On Job Until Reagan Leaves</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: First 9 grafs new with Lyng comments, picking up 7th graf pvs,
The USDA ... Also moving on general news wires.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Secretary Richard E. Lyng said
today he intends to stay on the job until the next administration
takes over Jan. 20.
   ``I'm going to be fairly busy up until the end of the year and
then for 20 days in January,'' Lyng said, adding that he had turned
down a number of speaking invitations. ``It would seem that in the
last two or three weeks (on the job) I might be of some help to my
successor.''
   Lyng had already passed the word to senior staff people that he
``has some unfinished work'' to do concerning trade talks and that
he and U.S. Trade Representative Clayton Yeutter will be busy
tidying up those affairs over the next few weeks, regardless of how
the presidential election turns out Tuesday.
   A special meeting of the 96 member countries of the General
Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, at which agriculture will be a
central focus, is scheduled to begin in Montreal on Dec. 5, for
example.
   Lyng also said that he wants to take some vacation time to be
with his family and then return to USDA for more work and a round of
farewells before bowing out.
   But gossip has persisted that if George Bush wins the election
Lyng may be prevailed upon to resign and head up a GOP transition
team at USDA, a job he did when Ronald Reagan won the White House
eight years ago.
   Lyng, 70, has said publicly for months that he plans to retire
when Reagan leaves office in January but had not spelled out what
role he might play in the event Bush wins the presidency.
   In an interview today, Lyng discounted rumors of resigning early
to head a Bush transition team.
   ``I don't think that would make much sense,'' Lyng said. ``I'm
here, and if they want me to help, I would.''
   The USDA rumor mill was provided additional grist this week. On
Tuesday, it was announced that David C. Lyons, Lyng's executive
assistant, will resign effective in ``late November'' and will go to
work in the private sector.
   Also, a monthly calendar of coming events involving USDA
officials showed that Lyng has several speaking engagements booked
through November but none after that. His last appearance before a
USDA group was shown as Nov. 29 at the department's annual outlook
conference.
   The calendar included the 70th annual meeting of the American
Farm Bureau Federation in San Antonio, Texas, on Jan. 8-12, but no
USDA participant was listed. A federation spokesman, John Lewis,
said Lyng is not on the program but ``would be welcome if he showed
up.''
   Lyng, a longtime friend of Reagan's, has been through the
revolving job door at USDA several times and is intimately
acquainted with agency functions, needs and the political byways of
departmental bureaucracy.
   In early 1969, when he was head of the California Department of
Agriculture and Reagan was governor, Lyng was named by President
Nixon as assistant secretary of agriculture for consumer and
marketing services, a job he held for four years.
   From 1973 to 1979, Lyng was president of the industry supported
American Meat Institute and worked for Reagan's 1980 presidential
campaign. As head of the transition team, Lyng helped ease the way
for John R. Block to take over as secretary of agriculture.
   Lyng became deputy secretary, the No. 2 job in the department. He
resigned in 1985 to establish his own consulting firm but returned
to USDA as secretary in March 1986 after Block's resignation.
   It is unclear who would succeed Lyng if Bush were elected.
Yeutter has been mentioned frequently as the leading candidate and
has expressed interest in the USDA job. However, some feel that Bush
might want Yeutter to stay on as U.S. trade representative, at least
for a while.
   Former Iowa congressman Cooper Evans, an early supporter of Bush,
is rated highly by some as a likely secretary of agriculture.
   Another on the GOP list of possibles is Robert Delano, Warsaw,
Va., a former president of the American Farm Bureau Federation, who
also has been active in the Bush-Quayle farm campaign.
   Secretaries of agriculture from the South have been rare,
according to USDA historian Doug Bowers. John A. Knebel from
Virginia, who succeeded Earl L. Butz for a brief period at the end
of 1976 and into January 1977, was the most recent _ and only
Southerner, if border state Missouri isn't counted.
   Four Missourians were secretaries of agriculture, the most recent
being Arthur Hyde in 1929-33, a former Missouri governor.
   Still another potential GOP choice is the department's current
No. 2 official, Deputy Secretary Peter Myers _ and he is also from
Missouri.
</TEXT>
