<1ST_LINE>d f BC-BakerHughes     11-03 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Baker Hughes,0201</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Baker Hughes Scraps Sale of Local Divisions</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baker Hughes Inc. has taken its BJ-Titan Services
and BJ Services International divisions off the market, citing
disappointingly low bids for the two pressure pumping businesses.
   Baker Hughes had announced in June it would sell the two Houston
divisions, which analysts had valued at about $200 million, as part
of its strategy to focus on core businesses in which it is a market
leader.
   Company president Jim Woods said in early October that Baker
Hughes had received three or four serious bids and was negotiating
with one of the bidders. But he declined to identify the firm or the
price.
   BJ-Titan and BJ Services International provide acidizing,
cementing and fracturing services used to complete and start
production from oil and natural gas wells. The divisions employ
about 2,600 people worldwide.
   Woods said in a statement Wednesday that ``with the deterioration
and uncertainty in international oil prices, the proposed purchase
prices of the divisions were below the company's expectations.''
   The company said it would continue to operate the two businesses
as usual and has no current plans to seek other bids.
</TEXT>
