<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   11-03 0344</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Open Higher, Grains Are Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures were modestly higher on
follow-through buying from Wednesday's strong rally while grain
futures were mixed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of
Trade.
   Soybeans for delivery in November leaped 18{ cents a bushel
Wednesday on rumors of substantial Soviet purchases of U.S.
soybeans, analysts said.
   After Wednesday's close, the Agriculture Department confirmed
that the Soviets had bought 250,000 metric tons of U.S. soybeans,
their first soybean purchase for delivery in the marketing year that
began Sept. 1.
   Bullish traders welcomed the news but analysts noted that the
pace of Soviet buying of U.S. grains was well below last year's
level.
   ``The market's pretty evenly divided,'' said Cathy Leow, a grain
markets analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York.
``Some people are very bullish'' based on the Soviet buying, ``but
others think (the soybean runup) is a seasonal, post-harvest rally.''
   Wheat was narrowly mixed and corn was a little lower due to a
lack of confirmation of rumored Russian buying of those commodities,
analysts said.
   In early trading, wheat was 1\ cents lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in December at $4.17{ a bushel; corn was {
cent to 1} cents lower with December at $2.84} a bushel; oats were 1
cent to 3 cents lower with December at $2.27} a bushel; soybeans
were { cent to 3 cents higher with November at $7.97{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were mixed in
early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .25 cent lower to .05 cent higher with December
at 73.37 cents a pound; feeder cattle were unchanged to .30 cent
lower with November at 81.65 cents a pound; live hogs were .12 cent
lower to .10 cent higher with December at 41.85 cents a pound;
frozen pork bellies were .10 cent lower to .55 cent higher with
February at 47.40 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly higher on Wednesday.
</TEXT>
