<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Gulf-Locusts     11-03 0373</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Gulf-Locusts,0386</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Saudi Arabia Expects Locust Invasions Until November</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RIYADH, Saudi Arabia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Saudi Arabia reported that locusts
were still invading its west coast Thursday and that weather
conditions would drive more across the Red Sea.
   But a major combat operation in motion since the first attack
Oct. 13 prevented the crop-devouring insects from penetrating the
interior of the kingdom, said a press statement from the Ministry of
Agriculture.
   ``The situation is reassuring at present and the ministry is
taking all effective measures to bar the locusts from moving toward
the Arab states,'' said the statement.
   In recent days, locust swarms were reported in Iraq, Iran,
northern Kuwait and in the central gulf around Bahrain and Qatar.
These countries have been on the alert with their own combat squads
and pesticides. All have reported the situation is under control.
   In Bahrain a ``hotline'' has been established to report sightings.
   Said Hassan Abdul-Karim, director of farmer services at the
Bahraini ministry of agriculture, ``The situation is all under
control. There is nothing now and the country is almost clean. Our
people have been surveying ... and there's nothing so far. ''
   Instructions circulated in Bahrain and the other countries have
not failed to remind residents not to pick the locusts for eating,
since they are considered a delicacy. Once sprayed, the locusts
become poisonous, said the instructions circulated through the media.
   The locust invasion which blew across the Red Sea from the east
African coast is believed the worst in 25 years.
   The Saudi statement said rainfall along an 875-mile stretch of
its Red Sea coast had helped the infestation while weather
conditions over Turkey produced north and northeasterly winds
``which might lead to continuation of the swarms reaching the
kingdom till November.''
   It said hundreds of ground squads equipped with sprayers and
insecticides and assisted by aerial squadrons arrested the locust
penetration into the interior ``and yet more swarms of the desert
locusts are still reaching the kingdom.''
   More swarms were also expected in light of the reports by the
World Food and Agriculture Organization which said that the locusts
were widespread in the Sudan and that the situation was critical and
deteriorating in Sudan, Mauritania, Mali, Senegal, Niger and Gambia.
</TEXT>
