<1ST_LINE>r f BC-MCorp     11-03 0275</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-MCorp,0286</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Bank Told To Plan Cash Shift</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal regulators are expected to order
MCorp to inject about $400 million into its troubled bank
subsidiaries, a move that will likely push the holding company into
bankruptcy court, reports published Thursday said.
   The Fort Worth Star-Telegram and the Wall Street Journal said the
Comptroller of the Currency notified most of MCorp's 25 banks last
week that it intends to demand they raise more capital.
   The Federal Reserve Board also ordered MCorp to draft a plan to
boost its banks' capital, the reports said.
   The $400 million amount was mentioned by both federal agencies,
along with the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp., which insures bank
deposits, they said.
   MCorp had no comment on the reports, spokesman George McCane said
Thursday. However, sources told the newspapers MCorp will file for
protection under Chapter 11 of federal bankruptcy laws if it
receives a permanent order for a cash transfer.
   ``If there is a direct order, or if certain events or actions by
regulators show that their intention is to order MCorp to move the
money, that would be interpreted as a reason for the company to seek
the protection of an independent referee,'' the Star-Telegram's
source said.
   MCorp, the second-largest bank holding company in Texas, posted a
record $517 million loss for the third quarter.
   MCorp has asked for federal help in a management-led
reorganization that would include $400 million from the holding
company, $400 million raised from private investors and shareholders
and an undetermined amount from the Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
Analysts estimate the FDIC would have to provide about $1 billion.
</TEXT>
