<HEAD>London Shares End Off 5.6 Points</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with closing prices</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices finished lower Thursday in moderate
trading amid a lack of buying.
   ``The buyers are out on strike,'' said a market maker, adding
that sentiment remainded guarded after two successive days of steep
declines.
   Shares were helped off intraday lows late in the session by a
stronger start to Wall Street and the revival of several recent bid
stories.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index closed off 5.6
points, or 0.3 percent, at 1,837.6.
   The index lost as much as 13.5 points in late morning before
steadying.
   The narrower Financial Times 30-share index ended off 6.1 points
at 1,489.5.
   Volume was 507.5 million shares, compared with the 428.8 million
shares traded Wednesday.
   The Dow Jones industrial average was up 16.18 points at 2,173.01
as the London session drew to a close. One dealer said the movement
higher in New York had given the London market ``an excuse to get
its toes wet and buy a bit.''
</TEXT>
