<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Britannia-Boeing     11-03 0133</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britannia-Boeing,0141</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britannia Airways Orders Boeing Planes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britannia Airways has ordered eight long-range
767-200 airplanes from Boeing Commercial Airlines and secured
options for eight more, a Britannia official announced today.
   Deliveries in the $500 million order are scheduled to begin in
February 1990, according to Dave Hopkins, managing director for
Britannia.
   ``The order also reflects Britannia's commitment to buying large,
superquiet aircraft which will help keep noise levels to a minimum
and also ease the problem of congested airspace by carrying more
passsengers in one movement,'' Hopkins said.
   In Britannia's seating configuration, the 767-200 will carry 273
passengers.
   Following its takeover of Orion Airways, Britannia will be
operating a fleet of 37 Boeing 737s and seven 767s.
   The announcement brings total orders for the Boeing 767 airplane
to 334.
</TEXT>
