<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market was briskly higher this
afternoon, buoyed by the dollar's steadiness after a recent steep
decline.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials was up 16.53 points at
2,173.36 at 2 p.m. EST, after rising gradually through the trading
session.
   Much of the advance was said to come from a surge in Sears
Roebuck, one of the components of the blue-chip indicator.
   Sears shares had soared 2] to 45], bolstered by unconfirmed
rumors that investor Ronald Perelman is poised to make a bid for the
giant retailer. Sears announced a major restructuring on Monday.
   Advancing issues outpaced declining ones by around 8 to 5 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 788 issues up, 563 down and 557
unchanged.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 107.65 million shares.
   Stocks have come under some pressure from the dollar's persistent
decline in recent days, which has raised fears that the Federal
Reserve could bolster the U.S. currency by nudging interest rates
higher.
   The dollar stabilized in foreign-exchange trading early today,
giving a lift to stock prices.
   ``The tone seems to be better,'' said Jack Baker, the head of
block trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   He noted, however, that activity continues to be dominated by
professional traders, with many institutional investors staying on
the sidelines.
   Through most of this week, trading has been dampened by the
market's anticipation of upcoming events: notably Friday's release
of U.S. unemployment data for October and the presidential election
next Tuesday.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks had
risen 0.39 to 157.39.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
0.09 at 299.74.
   Sears was the most actively traded issue on the NYSE. Among other
active issues on the exchange, RJR Nabisco had risen | to 87], AT&T
was up [ at 28~, Limited had risen 1 point to 27, Bank of America
had gained ] at 19 and Ford Motor was unchanged at 51].
   Kraft was down [ at 103], General Electric had slipped [ to 44{
and Reebok had lost | at 13{.
