<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 1435EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-StockFraud     11-03 0324</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stock Fraud,0335</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Grand Jury Charges Securities Firm and Its Chief With Manipulation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An investment firm and its founder were indicted
today on stock manipulation and other securities fraud charges in
connection with the sale of Fireman's Fund Corp. shares by American
Express Co. more than two years ago.
   The multiple-count indictment by the federal grand jury against
Salim B. Lewis and S.B. Lewis & Co. was an indirect outgrowth of the
Ivan Boesky insider trading scandal, and federal prosecutors said
others might be charged.
   U.S. Attorney Rudolph W. Giuliani told reporters the indictment
alleges that Lewis and other unidentified co-conspirators attempted
to manipulate upward the price of Fireman's Fund stock on May 8,
1986, the day American Express was to price an offering of Fireman's
Fund securities it wished to sell.
   ``One of the objects of the conspiracy was to make sure that
American Express maximized the proceeds that it received from that
offering,'' Giuliani said.
   Lewis, 49, is said to have a close relationship with American
Express, one of the biggest financial services companies and parent
of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., a leading Wall Street firm.
   Federal prosecutors would not elaborate on whether anybody inside
American Express played a role in the alleged conspiracy.
   Giuliani said some of the information for the indictment was
provided by Boyd L. Jefferies, a Los Angeles investment professional
who settled government charges of securities fraud in 1987 in
exchange for his cooperation in other investigations.
   Jefferies was exposed by Boesky, the most famous insider trader
in U.S. history. Now imprisoned, Boesky also is cooperating with the
government.
   A person answering the telephone at Lewis's New York office said
he was not available. Telephone messages left on his home answering
machine in Short Hills, N.J., were not immediately returned.
   American Express spokesman Lawrence A. Armour declined to comment
on the indictment, saying the company had not yet seen a copy of it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
