<DOCNO> AP881103-0301 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 1445EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-RJRNabisco 3rdLd-Writethru   11-03 0623</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-RJR Nabisco, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0640</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nabisco Managers Announce Nearly $21 Billion Bid</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS two grafs after 5th graf pvs `Kohlberg Kravis ..'' to
ADD that talks about joint bid terminated. Picks up 6th graf pvs
``Speculation that ..''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The management of RJR Nabisco Inc. today raised
the price tag on the largest corporate buyout in U.S. history,
announcing a nearly $21 billion cash and stock bid that tops an
earlier offer by Kohlberg Kravis Roberts & Co. for the food and
tobacco giant.
   R. Ross Johnson, president and chief executive officer of RJR
Nabisco, said in a two-paragraph statement that the management group
and its financial partners, Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. and Salomon
Inc., would offer stockholders $84 in cash and $8 worth of
securities for each Nabisco share outstanding.
   ``This is a full and fair price for stockholders,'' Johnson said.
``Our offer will be good for the company, its employees and the
communities we serve because our management group would bring the
continuity and knowhow needed to ensure the continued long-term
success of the business.''
   The management group put RJR Nabisco into ``play'' when it
announced two weeks ago that it was considering a $75-a-share, or
$17 billion, offer to take the company private.
   Kohlberg Kravis, the nation's leading leveraged buyout firm,
quickly followed with a tender offer to shareholders of $90 a share,
worth an estimated $20.3 billion.
   In a joint statement released shortly after Nabisco's bid was
announced, Johnson and Kohlberg Kravis said talks about a possible
joint bid had been terminated, although they left the door open to
``further discussions.''
   The two camps have talked off and on over the past two weeks
without success.
   Speculation that RJR Nabisco's management would unveil a higher
bid today had pushed up Nabisco stock $1.12{ a share before
Johnson's announcement and it rose 37{ cents more to $88 after the
statement was released.
   The Wall Street Journal had reported in today's editions that the
management group was close to topping the Kohlberg Kravis bid.
   The Journal said the group had talked with other food companies
and other investors, including Texas financier Robert Bass, about
joining in the bid.
   In addition, the Journal and the Atlanta Constitution also
reported that another leveraged buyout firm, Forstman Little & Co.,
was considering entering the battle.
   The Journal gave no attribution for Forstmann Little's interest
in bidding for RJR Nabisco, but said it was understood that the
investment concern had signed a confidential agreement with RJR
Nabisco's board allowing it to analyze some confidential financial
information.
   RJR Nabisco's board issued a statement Wednesday inviting other
interested parties to bid for the nation's 19th-largest industrial
concern, maker of such well-known brands as Winston cigarettes and
Oreo cookies.
   Charles Hugel, who is chairman of the committee of outside
directors appointed to review takeover proposals, said the panel
believed ``this will serve the best interest of all shareholders.''
   The financial world had been stunned when RJR Nabisco's
management announced it was considering the leveraged buyout, the
biggest corporate transaction of its kind in U.S. history.
   In a leveraged buyout, most of the purchase price is borrowed
money that is repaid with the acquired company's cash flow or asset
sales.
   The leaders of Kohlberg Kravis reportedly have fought the RJR
Nabisco battle because they are intent on retaining the firm's
preeminence in leveraged buyouts.
   But speculation has arisen that the firm might be under pressure
to withdraw from the bidding. Several institutional investors in the
firm's leveraged buyout fund, which would provide a small part of
the financing, are balking on the grounds that they believe the
firm's approach is hostile, even though it made its offer contingent
on getting support from RJR Nabisco's board.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
