<1ST_LINE>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   11-03 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Drift Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prices of most grain and soybean futures
drifted lower Thursday on the Chicago Board of Trade as traders
disappointed by the fitful pace of grain sales for export took
profits off the latest speculative rally.
   The Agriculture Department's confirmation late Wednesday of a
250,000-ton soybean sale to the Soviet Union provided some
consolation but the corn market registered frustration at the lack
of official word about a rumored sale of U.S. corn to the Soviets,
analysts said.
   ``The commercials who were buyers yesterday turned sellers and we
just saw some long liquidation in the market,'' said Cathy Leow, a
grain markets analyst with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New
York.
   The market's weakening tone also reflected expectations that the
USDA will revise upward its 1988 U.S. grain and soybean production
estimates, she said. That USDA crop report is due out next Wednesday.
   At the close, wheat was 1} cents lower to { cent higher with the
contract for delivery in December at $4.17 a bushel; corn was 4
cents lower to 1\ cents higher with December at $2.82{ a bushel;
oats were 6 cents to 8{ cents lower with December at $2.22 a bushel;
soybeans were 2 cents lower to 3\ cents higher with November at
$7.94 a bushel.
</TEXT>
