<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-MGMGrand     11-03 0281</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-MGM Grand,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kerkorian's New Casino-Airline Firm Lost $955,000 in 3rd Qtr.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Kathi Grohgan is spelled correctly</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   MGM Grand Inc., financier Kirk
Kerkorian's new casino and luxury airline firm, reported a loss of
$955,000 in its third quarter as a publicly traded company.
   The company said Thursday its sales for the period totaled $54.2
million on its three-plane airline business and two hotel-casinos in
Las Vegas.
   In its first nine months of operations, MGM Grand said its profit
was $356,000, or 2 cents a share.
   In 1987, before the company first sold stock, it lost $4.3
million in the third quarter and $8.3 million in the first three
quarters.
   Controller Kathi Grohgan attributed the latest loss to start-up
costs.
   The company, controlled by Kerkorian and taking its name from the
MGM Grand Hotel and Casino he used to own, consists of the MGM
Desert Inn and MGM Sands hotel-casinos in Las Vegas and the
all-first class MGM Grand Air.
   The hotel-casinos had sales of $48.2 million in the quarter. The
company has agreed to sell the MGM Sands to Interface Group of
Massachusetts for $110 million, but the deal is awaiting approval of
Nevada gambling regulators.
   The airline, which caters to the carriage trade by flying three
luxurious Boeing 727s between Los Angeles and New York, had sales of
$6 million in the third quarter, the company said. Three refurbished
DC-8s are to be added to the line.
   The company refused to release figures on the number of
passengers it carries, and the profit and loss figures are
consolidated results of the casino and airline operations.
   Kerkorian also controls movie maker MGM-UA Communications Co.
</TEXT>
