<1ST_LINE>u f PM-WallStreetClosing     11-03 0267</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street Closing,0280</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market rose briskly today, bolstered by
the dollar's steadiness after a recent prolonged decline.
   The advance was led by blue-chip issues, especially shares of
Sears Roebuck. Sears shares soared, bolstered by unconfirmed rumors
that investor Ronald Perelman is poised to make a bid for the giant
retailer. The company announced a major restructuring on Monday.
   Stocks have come under some pressure from the dollar's persistent
decline in recent days, which has raised fears that the Federal
Reserve could bolster the U.S. currency by nudging interest rates
higher.
   The dollar stabilized in foreign-exchange trading today, giving a
lift to stock prices.
   ``The tone seems to be better,'' said Jack Baker, the head of
block trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Bond prices also benefitted from the dollar's recovery, which
gave additional support to the stock market, analysts said. Another
positive factor was a decline in prices of key commodities, which
calmed inflationary fears.
   Market watchers noted, however, that activity continued to be
dominated by professional traders, with many institutional investors
staying on the sidelines.
   Through most of this week, trading has been dampened by the
market's anticipation of upcoming events: notably Friday's release
of U.S. unemployment data for October and the presidential election
next Tuesday.
   ``So far, so good _ but nothing to write home about yet,'' said
Bill Raftery, an analyst for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Some of the lift today also could have come from stock purchases
by traders not wanting to be caught short when the unemployment data
are published, he suggested.
</TEXT>
