<1ST_LINE>u f AM-MoneyFunds     11-03 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Money Funds,0362</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Money Funds Rose $1.35 Billion in Latest Week</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Interest rate figures reported by Donoghue's Money Fund Report
are for week ended Tuesday. All other figures are for the week ended
Wednesday.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Assets of the nation's 454 money market mutual
funds rose $1.35 billion in the latest week, the Investment Company
Institute said Thursday.
   The increase, to $271.96 billion in the seven-day period ended
Wednesday, followed a revised $270.61 billion increase in the funds'
assets the previous week, according to the Washington-based mutual
fund trade group.
   The funds' assets hit a record high $280.02 billion in the week
ended Feb. 24.
   The Investment Company Institute said that in the latest week,
assets of 223 general purpose funds rose $690.6 million to $86.32
billion, assets of 102 broker-dealer funds increased $553.9 million
to $114.93 billion, and assets of 129 institutional funds rose
$107.7 million to $70.71 billion.
   The seven-day average yield on money market mutual funds rose in
the week ended Tuesday to 7.55 percent from 7.54 percent the
previous week, according to Donoghue's Money Fund Report, a trade
journal based in Holliston, Mass.
   The 30-day average yield rose, to 7.51 percent from 7.50 percent,
Donoghue's said.
   The average maturity of the portfolios held by money funds was 37
days, unchanged from the previous week, Donoghue's said.
   Separately, the newsletter Bank Rate Monitor said its survey of
100 leading commercial banks, savings and loan assocations and
savings banks in the nation's 10 largest markets showed the
effective annual yield available on money market accounts rose to
6.08 percent as of Wednesday from 6.07 percent a week earlier.
   The North Palm Beach, Fla.-based newsletter said the effective
annual yield available on special savings accounts, called Super NOW
accounts, was unchanged at 5.12 percent.
   Bank Rate Monitor said the effective annual yield was 7.83
percent on six-month certificates of deposit, up from 7.82 percent
the previous week. Yields were 8.13 percent on 1-year CDs, up from
8.12 percent; 8.32 percent on 2{-year CDs, down from 8.33 percent;
and 8.54 percent on 5-year CDs, down from 8.56 percent.
</TEXT>
