<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0602</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steadiness in the dollar after a recent prolonged
decline helped boost the stock market Thursday.
   The advance was led by blue-chip issues. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials ended 13.51 points higher at 2,170.34, after rising
gradually through most of the session. The widely watched indicator
had been up more than 21 points at 3 p.m. EST, but gave ground just
before the close of trading.
   Much of the gain in the Dow average was attributed to a surge in
Sears Roebuck, one of its components.
   Sears shares soared 3 to 46, driven by unconfirmed rumors that
investor Ronald Perelman is poised to make a bid for the giant
retailer. Sears announced a major restructuring on Monday.
   In the broader market, advancing issues outpaced declines by
about 4 to 3 in nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed
stocks, with 781 issues up, 652 down and 545 unchanged.
   Stocks have come under some pressure from the dollar's persistent
decline in recent days, which has raised fears that the Federal
Reserve could bolster the currency by nudging interest rates higher.
   The dollar stabilized in foreign-exchange trading Thursday,
giving a lift to stock prices. The U.S. currency was quoted late in
New York at around 124.68 Japanese yen, up from 124.40 yen late
Wednesday.
   ``The tone seems to be better,'' said Jack Baker, the head of
block trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   Bond prices also benefited from the dollar's recovery, which gave
additional support to the stock market, analysts said. Another
positive factor was a decline in prices of gold and other key
commodities, which calmed inflationary fears.
   Market watchers noted, however, that activity continued to be
dominated by professional traders, with many institutional investors
staying on the sidelines.
   Through most of this week, trading has been dampened by the
market's anticipation of upcoming events: notably Friday's release
of U.S. unemployment data for October and the presidential election
next Tuesday.
   ``So far, so good _ but nothing to write home about yet,'' said
Bill Raftery, an analyst for Smith Barney, Harris Upham & Co.
   Some of the lift Thursday also could have come from stock
purchases by traders not wanting to be caught short when the
unemployment data are published, he suggested.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 152.98 million shares,
down from 161.30 million in Wednesday's session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trading at
regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market, totaled
182.48 million shares.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks edged
up 0.08 to 157.08.
   Sears was the most actively traded issue on the NYSE. Among other
active issues on the exchange, RJR Nabisco rose \ to 87, AT&T was
unchanged at 28}, Bank of America gained ] at 19 and K Mart advanced
| to 37\.
   Kraft lost \ at 103\, General Electric was down ] at 44\, Merck
slipped [ to 58~ and Ford Motor declined ~ to 50{.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index was down
0.03 at 299.80.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 0.16 to 321.51, and S&P's
500-stock composite index was up 0.14 at 279.20.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
advanced 0.99 to 382.77.
   The Wilshire Associates Equity Index, the market value of NYSE,
American and OTC issues, was up $1.425 billion, or 0.05 percent.
