<FILEID>AP-NR-11-03-88 2213EST</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-DisguisedTrader     11-03 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Disguised Trader,0432</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Sentenced In Disguised Trader Scheme At CBOT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Colorado man was sentenced Thursday to six years
in prison on charges he masterminded a scheme to defraud the Chicago
Board of Trade out of $320,000 by using a disguised trader with a
false mustache and forged documents.
   In sentencing Thompson B. Sanders and three other men, U.S.
District Judge Marvin Aspen said the case shows the Board of Trade
is ``ripe .. for corruption and manipulation,'' and that the trading
pits ``can be turned into cesspools.''
   But Scott Early, general counsel for the CBOT, said, ``The judge
has obviously seen a very limited part of the Board of Trade _ one
member.''
   Early said board officials began the probe of the 1986 scheme and
cooperated fully with the U.S. Attorney's office in the prosecution
of the case.
   The judge also fined Sanders $300,000.
   ``You went for the big kill, and you almost got away with it,''
Aspen told Sanders, 45.
   After a three-week trial, Sanders, a former grain trader who
operates a restaurant in Vail, Colo., was convicted in September of
conspiracy, wire fraud and interstate transporation of stolen
property.
   Sanders' lawyer, former U.S. Attorney Dan K. Webb, said he would
appeal.
   The other defendants had pleaded guilty and testified against
Sanders.
   Daniel Dewey, 39, the man who wore disguises to a restricted
trading pit at the CBOT, was given five years in prison and fined
$100,000; David Pelleu, 45, was sentenced to six months of work
release and fined $11,000; and Daniel Kolton, 24, was given five
years probation, 500 hours of community service and fined $2,500.
   Pelleu had helped make phony CBOT badges, while Kolton went on
the trading floor to act as Dewey's associate, Assistant U.S.
Attorney Thomas Durkin said.
   Aspen praised Pelleu for going to the FBI in January 1987 _ when
authorities complained their investigation had hit a dead end _ and
explaining the whole scheme.
   Prosecutors said the disguised Dewey traded U.S. Treasury bond
futures at the CBOT on four days in the summer of 1986. Dewey, of
Ashville, N.C., processed his winnings through Sanders' account at a
brokerage firm, but if Dewey had lost money, the trades wouldn't
have been processed and Dewey couldn't have been traced because of
his false identification, Durkin said.
   But Webb said Sanders set up the plan to shield income from his
wife's divorce lawyer. The defense attorney also maintained that the
scheme never defrauded any other brokers.
</TEXT>
