<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru f0285 11-03 0206</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0285,0213</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Edges Higher; Stocks Up Slightly</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates with morning Nikkei figure, later dollar trading,
comments.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite reported intervention by Japan's central
bank, the U.S. dollar strengthened only slightly against the
Japanese yen on Friday morning, although share prices edged higher.
   After opening at 124.72 yen, up 0.04 yen from Wednesday's close,
the dollar traded between 124.69-124.85 yen and was changing hands
at 124.77 yen by late morning.
   Stock and foreign exchange markets in Tokyo were closed Thursday
for Culture Day, a Japanese national holiday.
   Currency market sources said the Bank of Japan entered the market
Friday morning, buying an estimated $30 million to $50 million when
the U.S. currency was trading at around 124.80-124.85 yen.
   But Friday's central bank action, the fourth such intervention
this week, was ineffective in triggering the dollar's rally, with
the dollar trading around pre-intervention levels, the sources said.
   The Bank of Japan does not disclose its currency policies.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost 28.41
points Wednesday, finished the morning session up 4.17 points from
Wednesday's close at 27,989.43.
   Traders said the market was awaiting the October U.S. employment
figures scheduled for release later Friday in Washington.
